  <Name>k__BackingField: Acts
  fancyName: Acts of the Apostles
  nickname: act
  language: English
  lang: eng
  version: New Living Translation
  ver: NLT
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: The Promise of the Holy Spirit
      content: 'In my first book[COMMENT[0]] I told you, Theophilus, about everything
        Jesus began to do and teach '
      comments:
      - number: '1:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: The reference is to the Gospel of Luke.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'until the day he was taken up to heaven after giving his chosen apostles
        further instructions through the Holy Spirit. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During the forty days after he suffered and died, he appeared to
        the apostles from time to time, and he proved to them in many ways that he
        was actually alive. And he talked to them about the Kingdom of God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Once when he was eating with them, he commanded them, \n\t\u201CDo
        not leave Jerusalem until the Father sends you the gift he promised, as I
        told you before.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "John baptized with[COMMENT[0]]  \n\twater, but in just a few days
        you will be baptized with the Holy Spirit.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:5 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'in; '
        - ft: also in 1:5b.
          body: 
    - title: The Ascension of Jesus
      content: "So when the apostles were with Jesus, they kept asking him, \u201CLord,
        has the time come for you to free Israel and restore our kingdom?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He replied, \n\t\u201CThe Father alone has the authority to set those
        dates and times, and they are not for you to know.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But you will receive power when the Holy Spirit comes upon you. And
        you will be my witnesses, telling people about me everywhere\u2014in Jerusalem,
        throughout Judea, in Samaria, and to the ends of the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After saying this, he was taken up into a cloud while they were watching,
        and they could no longer see him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As they strained to see him rising into heaven, two white-robed men
        suddenly stood among them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMen of Galilee,\u201D they said, \u201Cwhy are you standing
        here staring into heaven? Jesus has been taken from you into heaven, but
        someday he will return from heaven in the same way you saw him go!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Matthias Replaces Judas
      content: 'Then the apostles returned to Jerusalem from the Mount of Olives,
        a distance of half a mile.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: "a Sabbath day\u2019s journey."
    - title: 
      content: "When they arrived, they went to the upstairs room of the house where
        they were staying.\n\tHere are the names of those who were present: Peter,
        John, James, Andrew, Philip, Thomas, Bartholomew, Matthew, James (son of
        Alphaeus), Simon (the zealot), and Judas (son of James). "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They all met together and were constantly united in prayer, along
        with Mary the mother of Jesus, several other women, and the brothers of Jesus.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During this time, when about 120 believers[COMMENT[0]] were together
        in one place, Peter stood up and addressed them. '
      comments:
      - number: '1:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: brothers.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBrothers,\u201D he said, \u201Cthe Scriptures had to be fulfilled
        concerning Judas, who guided those who arrested Jesus. This was predicted
        long ago by the Holy Spirit, speaking through King David. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Judas was one of us and shared in the ministry with us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(Judas had bought a field with the money he received for his treachery.
        Falling headfirst there, his body split open, spilling out all his intestines. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The news of his death spread to all the people of Jerusalem, and
        they gave the place the Aramaic name \n\tAkeldama, which means \u201CField
        of Blood.\u201D)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter continued, \u201CThis was written in the book of Psalms, where
        it says, \u2018Let his home become desolate, with no one living in it.\u2019
        It also says, \u2018Let someone else take his position.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:20 '
        contents:
        - ft: Pss 69:25; 109:8.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo now we must choose a replacement for Judas from among the
        men who were with us the entire time we were traveling with the Lord Jesus\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "from the time he was baptized by John until the day he was taken
        from us. Whoever is chosen will join us as a witness of Jesus\u2019 resurrection.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they nominated two men: Joseph called Barsabbas (also known as
        Justus) and Matthias. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then they all prayed, \u201CO Lord, you know every heart. Show us
        which of these men you have chosen "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "as an apostle to replace Judas in this ministry, for he has deserted
        us and gone where he belongs.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Then they cast lots, and Matthias was selected to become an apostle
        with the other eleven.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Holy Spirit Comes
      content: 'On the day of Pentecost[COMMENT[0]] all the believers were meeting
        together in one place. '
      comments:
      - number: '2:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: The Festival of Pentecost came 50 days after Passover (when Jesus was
            crucified).
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Suddenly, there was a sound from heaven like the roaring of a mighty
        windstorm, and it filled the house where they were sitting. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then, what looked like flames or tongues of fire appeared and settled
        on each of them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And everyone present was filled with the Holy Spirit and began speaking
        in other languages,[COMMENT[0]] as the Holy Spirit gave them this ability.  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:4 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: in other tongues.
    - title: 
      content: 'At that time there were devout Jews from every nation living in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they heard the loud noise, everyone came running, and they were
        bewildered to hear their own languages being spoken by the believers.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They were completely amazed. \u201CHow can this be?\u201D they exclaimed.
        \u201CThese people are all from Galilee, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and yet we hear them speaking in our own native languages! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Here we are\u2014Parthians, Medes, Elamites, people from Mesopotamia,
        Judea, Cappadocia, Pontus, the province of Asia, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Phrygia, Pamphylia, Egypt, and the areas of Libya around Cyrene,
        visitors from Rome '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "(both Jews and converts to Judaism), Cretans, and Arabs. And we all
        hear these people speaking in our own languages about the wonderful things
        God has done!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They stood there amazed and perplexed. \u201CWhat can this mean?\u201D
        they asked each other.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But others in the crowd ridiculed them, saying, \u201CThey\u2019re
        just drunk, that\u2019s all!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Peter Preaches to the Crowd
      content: "Then Peter stepped forward with the eleven other apostles and shouted
        to the crowd, \u201CListen carefully, all of you, fellow Jews and residents
        of Jerusalem! Make no mistake about this. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These people are not drunk, as some of you are assuming. Nine o\u2019clock
        in the morning is much too early for that. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'No, what you see was predicted long ago by the prophet Joel:  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018In the last days,\u2019 God says,\n\t\u2018I will pour out
        my Spirit upon all people.\n\tYour sons and daughters will prophesy.\n\tYour
        young men will see visions,\n\tand your old men will dream dreams.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In those days I will pour out my Spirit\n\teven on my servants\u2014men
        and women alike\u2014\n\tand they will prophesy.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I will cause wonders in the heavens above\n\tand signs on the
        earth below\u2014\n\tblood and fire and clouds of smoke.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The sun will become dark,\n\tand the moon will turn blood red\n\tbefore
        that great and glorious day of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> arrives.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But everyone who calls on the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\twill
        be saved.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:17-21 '
        contents:
        - ft: Joel 2:28-32.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPeople of Israel, listen! God publicly endorsed Jesus the Nazarene[COMMENT[0]]
        by doing powerful miracles, wonders, and signs through him, as you well know. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Jesus of Nazareth.
    - title: 
      content: 'But God knew what would happen, and his prearranged plan was carried
        out when Jesus was betrayed. With the help of lawless Gentiles, you nailed
        him to a cross and killed him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But God released him from the horrors of death and raised him back
        to life, for death could not keep him in its grip. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "King David said this about him:\n\t\u2018I see that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is always with me.\n\tI will not be shaken, for he is right beside me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No wonder my heart is glad,\n\tand my tongue shouts his praises!\n\tMy
        body rests in hope.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For you will not leave my soul among the dead[COMMENT[0]]or allow
        your Holy One to rot in the grave.  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:27 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'in Hades; '
        - ft: also in 2:31.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "You have shown me the way of life,\n\tand you will fill me with the
        joy of your presence.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:25-28 '
        contents:
        - ft: Ps 16:8-11 (Greek version).
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDear brothers, think about this! You can be sure that the patriarch
        David wasn\u2019t referring to himself, for he died and was buried, and his
        tomb is still here among us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But he was a prophet, and he knew God had promised with an oath that
        one of David\u2019s own descendants would sit on his throne. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David was looking into the future and speaking of the Messiah\u2019s
        resurrection. He was saying that God would not leave him among the dead or
        allow his body to rot in the grave.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGod raised Jesus from the dead, and we are all witnesses of
        this. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now he is exalted to the place of highest honor in heaven, at God\u2019s
        right hand. And the Father, as he had promised, gave him the Holy Spirit
        to pour out upon us, just as you see and hear today. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For David himself never ascended into heaven, yet he said,\n\t\u2018The
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to my Lord,\n\t\u201CSit in the place of
        honor at my right hand  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "until I humble your enemies,\n\tmaking them a footstool under your
        feet.\u201D\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:34-35 '
        contents:
        - ft: Ps 110:1.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo let everyone in Israel know for certain that God has made
        this Jesus, whom you crucified, to be both Lord and Messiah!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter\u2019s words pierced their hearts, and they said to him and
        to the other apostles, \u201CBrothers, what should we do?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter replied, \u201CEach of you must repent of your sins and turn
        to God, and be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ for the forgiveness of
        your sins. Then you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This promise is to you, to your children, and to those far away[COMMENT[0]]\u2014all
        who have been called by the Lord our God.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '2:39 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'and to people far in the future, '
        - ft: 'or '
          body: and to the Gentiles.
    - title: 
      content: "Then Peter continued preaching for a long time, strongly urging all
        his listeners, \u201CSave yourselves from this crooked generation!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Those who believed what Peter said were baptized and added to the
        church that day\u2014about 3,000 in all.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Believers Form a Community
      content: "All the believers devoted themselves to the apostles\u2019 teaching,
        and to fellowship, and to sharing in meals (including the Lord\u2019s Supper[COMMENT[0]]),
        and to prayer.  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:42 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'the breaking of bread; '
        - ft: also in 2:46.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'A deep sense of awe came over them all, and the apostles performed
        many miraculous signs and wonders. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And all the believers met together in one place and shared everything
        they had. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They sold their property and possessions and shared the money with
        those in need. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They worshiped together at the Temple each day, met in homes for
        the Lord\u2019s Supper, and shared their meals with great joy and generosity[COMMENT[0]]\u2014 "
      comments:
      - number: '2:46 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: and sincere hearts.
    - title: 
      content: all the while praising God and enjoying the goodwill of all the people.
        And each day the Lord added to their fellowship those who were being saved.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Peter Heals a Crippled Beggar
      content: "Peter and John went to the Temple one afternoon to take part in the
        three o\u2019clock prayer service. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As they approached the Temple, a man lame from birth was being carried
        in. Each day he was put beside the Temple gate, the one called the Beautiful
        Gate, so he could beg from the people going into the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When he saw Peter and John about to enter, he asked them for some
        money.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter and John looked at him intently, and Peter said, \u201CLook
        at us!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The lame man looked at them eagerly, expecting some money. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Peter said, \u201CI don\u2019t have any silver or gold for you.
        But I\u2019ll give you what I have. In the name of Jesus Christ the Nazarene,[COMMENT[0]]
        get up and[COMMENT[1]] walk!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:6a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Jesus Christ of Nazareth.
      - number: '3:6b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts do not include '
          body: get up and.
    - title: 
      content: "Then Peter took the lame man by the right hand and helped him up.
        And as he did, the man\u2019s feet and ankles were instantly healed and strengthened. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He jumped up, stood on his feet, and began to walk! Then, walking,
        leaping, and praising God, he went into the Temple with them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the people saw him walking and heard him praising God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they realized he was the lame beggar they had seen so often
        at the Beautiful Gate, they were absolutely astounded! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They all rushed out in amazement to Solomon\u2019s Colonnade, where
        the man was holding tightly to Peter and John.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Peter Preaches in the Temple
      content: "Peter saw his opportunity and addressed the crowd. \u201CPeople of
        Israel,\u201D he said, \u201Cwhat is so surprising about this? And why stare
        at us as though we had made this man walk by our own power or godliness? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For it is the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob\u2014the God of all
        our ancestors\u2014who has brought glory to his servant Jesus by doing this.
        This is the same Jesus whom you handed over and rejected before Pilate, despite
        Pilate\u2019s decision to release him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You rejected this holy, righteous one and instead demanded the release
        of a murderer. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You killed the author of life, but God raised him from the dead.
        And we are witnesses of this fact!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThrough faith in the name of Jesus, this man was healed\u2014and
        you know how crippled he was before. Faith in Jesus\u2019 name has healed
        him before your very eyes.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFriends,[COMMENT[0]] I realize that what you and your leaders
        did to Jesus was done in ignorance. "
      comments:
      - number: '3:17 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Brothers.
    - title: 
      content: "But God was fulfilling what all the prophets had foretold about the
        Messiah\u2014that he must suffer these things. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now repent of your sins and turn to God, so that your sins may be
        wiped away. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then times of refreshment will come from the presence of the Lord,
        and he will again send you Jesus, your appointed Messiah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For he must remain in heaven until the time for the final restoration
        of all things, as God promised long ago through his holy prophets. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses said, \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God will raise
        up for you a Prophet like me from among your own people. Listen carefully
        to everything he tells you.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: Deut 18:15.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses said, \u2018Anyone who will not listen to that Prophet
        will be completely cut off from God\u2019s people.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:23 '
        contents:
        - ft: Deut 18:19; Lev 23:29.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CStarting with Samuel, every prophet spoke about what is happening
        today. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You are the children of those prophets, and you are included in the
        covenant God promised to your ancestors. For God said to Abraham, \u2018Through
        your descendants[COMMENT[0]] all the families on earth will be blessed.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: '3:25 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'your seed; '
        - ft: see Gen 12:3; 22:18.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "When God raised up his servant, Jesus, he sent him first to you people
        of Israel, to bless you by turning each of you back from your sinful ways.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Peter and John before the Council
      content: 'While Peter and John were speaking to the people, they were confronted
        by the priests, the captain of the Temple guard, and some of the Sadducees. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These leaders were very disturbed that Peter and John were teaching
        the people that through Jesus there is a resurrection of the dead. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They arrested them and, since it was already evening, put them in
        jail until morning. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But many of the people who heard their message believed it, so the
        number of men who believed now totaled about 5,000.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next day the council of all the rulers and elders and teachers
        of religious law met in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Annas the high priest was there, along with Caiaphas, John, Alexander,
        and other relatives of the high priest. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They brought in the two disciples and demanded, \u201CBy what power,
        or in whose name, have you done this?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Peter, filled with the Holy Spirit, said to them, \u201CRulers
        and elders of our people, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "are we being questioned today because we\u2019ve done a good deed
        for a crippled man? Do you want to know how he was healed? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Let me clearly state to all of you and to all the people of Israel
        that he was healed by the powerful name of Jesus Christ the Nazarene,[COMMENT[0]]
        the man you crucified but whom God raised from the dead. '
      comments:
      - number: '4:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Jesus Christ of Nazareth.
    - title: 
      content: "For Jesus is the one referred to in the Scriptures, where it says,\n\t\u2018The
        stone that you builders rejected\n\thas now become the cornerstone.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:11 '
        contents:
        - ft: Ps 118:22.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "There is salvation in no one else! God has given no other name under
        heaven by which we must be saved.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The members of the council were amazed when they saw the boldness
        of Peter and John, for they could see that they were ordinary men with no
        special training in the Scriptures. They also recognized them as men who
        had been with Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But since they could see the man who had been healed standing right
        there among them, there was nothing the council could say. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they ordered Peter and John out of the council chamber[COMMENT[0]]
        and conferred among themselves.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the Sanhedrin.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat should we do with these men?\u201D they asked each other.
        \u201CWe can\u2019t deny that they have performed a miraculous sign, and
        everybody in Jerusalem knows about it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But to keep them from spreading their propaganda any further, we
        must warn them not to speak to anyone in Jesus\u2019 name again.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they called the apostles back in and commanded them never again
        to speak or teach in the name of Jesus.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Peter and John replied, \u201CDo you think God wants us to obey
        you rather than him? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We cannot stop telling about everything we have seen and heard.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The council then threatened them further, but they finally let them
        go because they didn\u2019t know how to punish them without starting a riot.
        For everyone was praising God "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "for this miraculous sign\u2014the healing of a man who had been lame
        for more than forty years.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Believers Pray for Courage
      content: 'As soon as they were freed, Peter and John returned to the other
        believers and told them what the leading priests and elders had said. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they heard the report, all the believers lifted their voices
        together in prayer to God: \u201CO Sovereign Lord, Creator of heaven and
        earth, the sea, and everything in them\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "you spoke long ago by the Holy Spirit through our ancestor David,
        your servant, saying,\n\t\u2018Why were the nations so angry?\n\tWhy did
        they waste their time with futile plans?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The kings of the earth prepared for battle;\n\tthe rulers gathered
        together\n\tagainst the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\tand against his Messiah.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:25-26 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'his anointed one; '
        - ft: 'or '
          body: 'his Christ. '
        - ft: Ps 2:1-2.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn fact, this has happened here in this very city! For Herod
        Antipas, Pontius Pilate the governor, the Gentiles, and the people of Israel
        were all united against Jesus, your holy servant, whom you anointed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But everything they did was determined beforehand according to your
        will. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And now, O Lord, hear their threats, and give us, your servants,
        great boldness in preaching your word. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Stretch out your hand with healing power; may miraculous signs and
        wonders be done through the name of your holy servant Jesus.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After this prayer, the meeting place shook, and they were all filled
        with the Holy Spirit. Then they preached the word of God with boldness.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Believers Share Their Possessions
      content: 'All the believers were united in heart and mind. And they felt that
        what they owned was not their own, so they shared everything they had. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The apostles testified powerfully to the resurrection of the Lord
        Jesus, and God\u2019s great blessing was upon them all. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There were no needy people among them, because those who owned land
        or houses would sell them '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and bring the money to the apostles to give to those in need.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For instance, there was Joseph, the one the apostles nicknamed Barnabas
        (which means \u201CSon of Encouragement\u201D). He was from the tribe of
        Levi and came from the island of Cyprus. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: He sold a field he owned and brought the money to the apostles.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Ananias and Sapphira
      content: 'But there was a certain man named Ananias who, with his wife, Sapphira,
        sold some property. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He brought part of the money to the apostles, claiming it was the
        full amount. With his wife\u2019s consent, he kept the rest.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Peter said, \u201CAnanias, why have you let Satan fill your
        heart? You lied to the Holy Spirit, and you kept some of the money for yourself. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The property was yours to sell or not sell, as you wished. And after
        selling it, the money was also yours to give away. How could you do a thing
        like this? You weren\u2019t lying to us but to God!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as Ananias heard these words, he fell to the floor and died.
        Everyone who heard about it was terrified. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then some young men got up, wrapped him in a sheet, and took him
        out and buried him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'About three hours later his wife came in, not knowing what had happened. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter asked her, \u201CWas this the price you and your husband received
        for your land?\u201D\n\t\u201CYes,\u201D she replied, \u201Cthat was the
        price.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Peter said, \u201CHow could the two of you even think of conspiring
        to test the Spirit of the Lord like this? The young men who buried your husband
        are just outside the door, and they will carry you out, too.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Instantly, she fell to the floor and died. When the young men came
        in and saw that she was dead, they carried her out and buried her beside
        her husband. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Great fear gripped the entire church and everyone else who heard
        what had happened.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Apostles Heal Many
      content: "The apostles were performing many miraculous signs and wonders among
        the people. And all the believers were meeting regularly at the Temple in
        the area known as Solomon\u2019s Colonnade. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But no one else dared to join them, even though all the people had
        high regard for them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yet more and more people believed and were brought to the Lord\u2014crowds
        of both men and women. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As a result of the apostles\u2019 work, sick people were brought
        out into the streets on beds and mats so that Peter\u2019s shadow might fall
        across some of them as he went by. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Crowds came from the villages around Jerusalem, bringing their sick
        and those possessed by evil[COMMENT[0]] spirits, and they were all healed.  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: unclean.
    - title: The Apostles Meet Opposition
      content: 'The high priest and his officials, who were Sadducees, were filled
        with jealousy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They arrested the apostles and put them in the public jail. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But an angel of the Lord came at night, opened the gates of the jail,
        and brought them out. Then he told them, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo to the Temple and give the people this message of life!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So at daybreak the apostles entered the Temple, as they were told,
        and immediately began teaching.\n\tWhen the high priest and his officials
        arrived, they convened the high council[COMMENT[0]]\u2014the full assembly
        of the elders of Israel. Then they sent for the apostles to be brought from
        the jail for trial. "
      comments:
      - number: '5:21 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'Sanhedrin; '
        - ft: also in 5:27, 41.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the Temple guards went to the jail, the men were gone. So
        they returned to the council and reported, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe jail was securely locked, with the guards standing outside,
        but when we opened the gates, no one was there!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the captain of the Temple guard and the leading priests heard
        this, they were perplexed, wondering where it would all end. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then someone arrived with startling news: \u201CThe men you put in
        jail are standing in the Temple, teaching the people!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The captain went with his Temple guards and arrested the apostles,
        but without violence, for they were afraid the people would stone them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they brought the apostles before the high council, where the
        high priest confronted them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe gave you strict orders never again to teach in this man\u2019s
        name!\u201D he said. \u201CInstead, you have filled all Jerusalem with your
        teaching about him, and you want to make us responsible for his death!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Peter and the apostles replied, \u201CWe must obey God rather
        than any human authority. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The God of our ancestors raised Jesus from the dead after you killed
        him by hanging him on a cross.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:30 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: on a tree.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then God put him in the place of honor at his right hand as Prince
        and Savior. He did this so the people of Israel would repent of their sins
        and be forgiven. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We are witnesses of these things and so is the Holy Spirit, who is
        given by God to those who obey him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they heard this, the high council was furious and decided to
        kill them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But one member, a Pharisee named Gamaliel, who was an expert in religious
        law and respected by all the people, stood up and ordered that the men be
        sent outside the council chamber for a while. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said to his colleagues, \u201CMen of Israel, take care what
        you are planning to do to these men! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some time ago there was that fellow Theudas, who pretended to be
        someone great. About 400 others joined him, but he was killed, and all his
        followers went their various ways. The whole movement came to nothing. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After him, at the time of the census, there was Judas of Galilee.
        He got people to follow him, but he was killed, too, and all his followers
        were scattered.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo my advice is, leave these men alone. Let them go. If they
        are planning and doing these things merely on their own, it will soon be
        overthrown. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if it is from God, you will not be able to overthrow them. You
        may even find yourselves fighting against God!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The others accepted his advice. They called in the apostles and had
        them flogged. Then they ordered them never again to speak in the name of
        Jesus, and they let them go.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The apostles left the high council rejoicing that God had counted
        them worthy to suffer disgrace for the name of Jesus.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:41 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: for the name.
    - title: 
      content: "And every day, in the Temple and from house to house, they continued
        to teach and preach this message: \u201CJesus is the Messiah.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Seven Men Chosen to Serve
      content: 'But as the believers[COMMENT[0]] rapidly multiplied, there were rumblings
        of discontent. The Greek-speaking believers complained about the Hebrew-speaking
        believers, saying that their widows were being discriminated against in the
        daily distribution of food.  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'disciples; '
        - ft: also in 6:2, 7.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "So the Twelve called a meeting of all the believers. They said, \u201CWe
        apostles should spend our time teaching the word of God, not running a food
        program. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And so, brothers, select seven men who are well respected and are
        full of the Spirit and wisdom. We will give them this responsibility. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then we apostles can spend our time in prayer and teaching the word.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Everyone liked this idea, and they chose the following: Stephen (a
        man full of faith and the Holy Spirit), Philip, Procorus, Nicanor, Timon,
        Parmenas, and Nicolas of Antioch (an earlier convert to the Jewish faith). '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These seven were presented to the apostles, who prayed for them as
        they laid their hands on them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So God\u2019s message continued to spread. The number of believers
        greatly increased in Jerusalem, and many of the Jewish priests were converted,
        too.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Stephen Is Arrested
      content: "Stephen, a man full of God\u2019s grace and power, performed amazing
        miracles and signs among the people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But one day some men from the Synagogue of Freed Slaves, as it was
        called, started to debate with him. They were Jews from Cyrene, Alexandria,
        Cilicia, and the province of Asia. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'None of them could stand against the wisdom and the Spirit with which
        Stephen spoke.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they persuaded some men to lie about Stephen, saying, \u201CWe
        heard him blaspheme Moses, and even God.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This roused the people, the elders, and the teachers of religious
        law. So they arrested Stephen and brought him before the high council.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'Sanhedrin; '
        - ft: also in 6:15.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "The lying witnesses said, \u201CThis man is always speaking against
        the holy Temple and against the law of Moses. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We have heard him say that this Jesus of Nazareth[COMMENT[0]] will
        destroy the Temple and change the customs Moses handed down to us.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Jesus the Nazarene.
    - title: 
      content: "At this point everyone in the high council stared at Stephen, because
        his face became as bright as an angel\u2019s."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Stephen Addresses the Council
      content: "Then the high priest asked Stephen, \u201CAre these accusations true?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This was Stephen\u2019s reply: \u201CBrothers and fathers, listen
        to me. Our glorious God appeared to our ancestor Abraham in Mesopotamia before
        he settled in Haran.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Mesopotamia '
        - ft: 'was the region now called Iraq. '
          body: 'Haran '
        - ft: was a city in what is now called Syria.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "God told him, \u2018Leave your native land and your relatives, and
        come into the land that I will show you.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:3 '
        contents:
        - ft: Gen 12:1.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'So Abraham left the land of the Chaldeans and lived in Haran until
        his father died. Then God brought him here to the land where you now live.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut God gave him no inheritance here, not even one square foot
        of land. God did promise, however, that eventually the whole land would belong
        to Abraham and his descendants\u2014even though he had no children yet. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'God also told him that his descendants would live in a foreign land,
        where they would be oppressed as slaves for 400 years. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018But I will punish the nation that enslaves them,\u2019 God
        said, \u2018and in the end they will come out and worship me here in this
        place.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:5-7 '
        contents:
        - ft: Gen 12:7; 15:13-14; Exod 3:12.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGod also gave Abraham the covenant of circumcision at that
        time. So when Abraham became the father of Isaac, he circumcised him on the
        eighth day. And the practice was continued when Isaac became the father of
        Jacob, and when Jacob became the father of the twelve patriarchs of the Israelite
        nation.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese patriarchs were jealous of their brother Joseph, and
        they sold him to be a slave in Egypt. But God was with him "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and rescued him from all his troubles. And God gave him favor before
        Pharaoh, king of Egypt. God also gave Joseph unusual wisdom, so that Pharaoh
        appointed him governor over all of Egypt and put him in charge of the palace.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut a famine came upon Egypt and Canaan. There was great misery,
        and our ancestors ran out of food. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob heard that there was still grain in Egypt, so he sent his sons\u2014our
        ancestors\u2014to buy some. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The second time they went, Joseph revealed his identity to his brothers,[COMMENT[0]]
        and they were introduced to Pharaoh. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Other manuscripts read '
          body: Joseph was recognized by his brothers.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joseph sent for his father, Jacob, and all his relatives to
        come to Egypt, seventy-five persons in all. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob went to Egypt. He died there, as did our ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Their bodies were taken to Shechem and buried in the tomb Abraham
        had bought for a certain price from Hamor\u2019s sons in Shechem.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAs the time drew near when God would fulfill his promise to
        Abraham, the number of our people in Egypt greatly increased. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But then a new king came to the throne of Egypt who knew nothing
        about Joseph. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This king exploited our people and oppressed them, forcing parents
        to abandon their newborn babies so they would die.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAt that time Moses was born\u2014a beautiful child in God\u2019s
        eyes. His parents cared for him at home for three months. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they had to abandon him, Pharaoh\u2019s daughter adopted him
        and raised him as her own son. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses was taught all the wisdom of the Egyptians, and he was powerful
        in both speech and action.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COne day when Moses was forty years old, he decided to visit
        his relatives, the people of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He saw an Egyptian mistreating an Israelite. So Moses came to the
        man\u2019s defense and avenged him, killing the Egyptian. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses assumed his fellow Israelites would realize that God had sent
        him to rescue them, but they didn\u2019t.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe next day he visited them again and saw two men of Israel
        fighting. He tried to be a peacemaker. \u2018Men,\u2019 he said, \u2018you
        are brothers. Why are you fighting each other?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut the man in the wrong pushed Moses aside. \u2018Who made
        you a ruler and judge over us?\u2019 he asked. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Are you going to kill me as you killed that Egyptian yesterday?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Moses heard that, he fled the country and lived as a foreigner
        in the land of Midian. There his two sons were born.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CForty years later, in the desert near Mount Sinai, an angel
        appeared to Moses in the flame of a burning bush. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Moses saw it, he was amazed at the sight. As he went to take
        a closer look, the voice of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> called out to
        him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018I am the God of your ancestors\u2014the God of Abraham, Isaac,
        and Jacob.\u2019 Moses shook with terror and did not dare to look.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to him, \u2018Take
        off your sandals, for you are standing on holy ground. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have certainly seen the oppression of my people in Egypt. I have
        heard their groans and have come down to rescue them. Now go, for I am sending
        you back to Egypt.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:31-34 '
        contents:
        - ft: Exod 3:5-10.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo God sent back the same man his people had previously rejected
        when they demanded, \u2018Who made you a ruler and judge over us?\u2019 Through
        the angel who appeared to him in the burning bush, God sent Moses to be their
        ruler and savior. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And by means of many wonders and miraculous signs, he led them out
        of Egypt, through the Red Sea, and through the wilderness for forty years.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMoses himself told the people of Israel, \u2018God will raise
        up for you a Prophet like me from among your own people.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:37 '
        contents:
        - ft: Deut 18:15.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Moses was with our ancestors, the assembly of God\u2019s people in
        the wilderness, when the angel spoke to him at Mount Sinai. And there Moses
        received life-giving words to pass on to us.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:38 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: to you.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut our ancestors refused to listen to Moses. They rejected
        him and wanted to return to Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They told Aaron, \u2018Make us some gods who can lead us, for we
        don\u2019t know what has become of this Moses, who brought us out of Egypt.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they made an idol shaped like a calf, and they sacrificed to it
        and celebrated over this thing they had made. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God turned away from them and abandoned them to serve the stars
        of heaven as their gods! In the book of the prophets it is written,\n\t\u2018Was
        it to me you were bringing sacrifices and offerings\n\tduring those forty
        years in the wilderness, Israel?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No, you carried your pagan gods\u2014\n\tthe shrine of Molech,\n\tthe
        star of your god Rephan,\n\tand the images you made to worship them.\n\tSo
        I will send you into exile\n\tas far away as Babylon.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:42-43 '
        contents:
        - ft: Amos 5:25-27 (Greek version).
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COur ancestors carried the Tabernacle[COMMENT[0]] with them
        through the wilderness. It was constructed according to the plan God had
        shown to Moses. "
      comments:
      - number: '7:44 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the tent of witness.
    - title: 
      content: 'Years later, when Joshua led our ancestors in battle against the
        nations that God drove out of this land, the Tabernacle was taken with them
        into their new territory. And it stayed there until the time of King David.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDavid found favor with God and asked for the privilege of building
        a permanent Temple for the God of Jacob.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:46 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: the house of Jacob.
    - title: 
      content: 'But it was Solomon who actually built it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "However, the Most High doesn\u2019t live in temples made by human
        hands. As the prophet says,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Heaven is my throne,\n\tand the earth is my footstool.\n\tCould
        you build me a temple as good as that?\u2019\n\tasks the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.\n\t\u2018Could
        you build me such a resting place?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Didn\u2019t my hands make both heaven and earth?\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:49-50 '
        contents:
        - ft: Isa 66:1-2.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou stubborn people! You are heathen[COMMENT[0]] at heart and
        deaf to the truth. Must you forever resist the Holy Spirit? That\u2019s what
        your ancestors did, and so do you! "
      comments:
      - number: '7:51 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: uncircumcised.
    - title: 
      content: "Name one prophet your ancestors didn\u2019t persecute! They even
        killed the ones who predicted the coming of the Righteous One\u2014the Messiah
        whom you betrayed and murdered. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You deliberately disobeyed God\u2019s law, even though you received
        it from the hands of angels.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Jewish leaders were infuriated by Stephen\u2019s accusation,
        and they shook their fists at him in rage.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:54 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: they were grinding their teeth against him.
    - title: 
      content: "But Stephen, full of the Holy Spirit, gazed steadily into heaven
        and saw the glory of God, and he saw Jesus standing in the place of honor
        at God\u2019s right hand. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And he told them, \u201CLook, I see the heavens opened and the Son
        of Man standing in the place of honor at God\u2019s right hand!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they put their hands over their ears and began shouting. They
        rushed at him '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and dragged him out of the city and began to stone him. His accusers
        took off their coats and laid them at the feet of a young man named Saul.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:58 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Saul '
        - ft: is later called Paul; see 13:9.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "As they stoned him, Stephen prayed, \u201CLord Jesus, receive my
        spirit.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He fell to his knees, shouting, \u201CLord, don\u2019t charge them
        with this sin!\u201D And with that, he died."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: 'Saul was one of the witnesses, and he agreed completely with the
        killing of Stephen.A great wave of persecution began that day, sweeping over
        the church in Jerusalem; and all the believers except the apostles were scattered
        through the regions of Judea and Samaria. '
      comments: []
    - title: Persecution Scatters the Believers
      content: '(Some devout men came and buried Stephen with great mourning.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Saul was going everywhere to destroy the church. He went from
        house to house, dragging out both men and women to throw them into prison.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Philip Preaches in Samaria
      content: 'But the believers who were scattered preached the Good News about
        Jesus wherever they went. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Philip, for example, went to the city of Samaria and told the people
        there about the Messiah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Crowds listened intently to Philip because they were eager to hear
        his message and see the miraculous signs he did. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Many evil[COMMENT[0]] spirits were cast out, screaming as they left
        their victims. And many who had been paralyzed or lame were healed. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:7 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: unclean.
    - title: 
      content: 'So there was great joy in that city.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A man named Simon had been a sorcerer there for many years, amazing
        the people of Samaria and claiming to be someone great. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Everyone, from the least to the greatest, often spoke of him as \u201Cthe
        Great One\u2014the Power of God.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They listened closely to him because for a long time he had astounded
        them with his magic.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But now the people believed Philip\u2019s message of Good News concerning
        the Kingdom of God and the name of Jesus Christ. As a result, many men and
        women were baptized. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Simon himself believed and was baptized. He began following
        Philip wherever he went, and he was amazed by the signs and great miracles
        Philip performed.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the apostles in Jerusalem heard that the people of Samaria had
        accepted God\u2019s message, they sent Peter and John there. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as they arrived, they prayed for these new believers to receive
        the Holy Spirit. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Holy Spirit had not yet come upon any of them, for they had only
        been baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Peter and John laid their hands upon these believers, and they
        received the Holy Spirit.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Simon saw that the Spirit was given when the apostles laid their
        hands on people, he offered them money to buy this power. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLet me have this power, too,\u201D he exclaimed, \u201Cso that
        when I lay my hands on people, they will receive the Holy Spirit!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Peter replied, \u201CMay your money be destroyed with you for
        thinking God\u2019s gift can be bought! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You can have no part in this, for your heart is not right with God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Repent of your wickedness and pray to the Lord. Perhaps he will forgive
        your evil thoughts, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "for I can see that you are full of bitter jealousy and are held captive
        by sin.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPray to the Lord for me,\u201D Simon exclaimed, \u201Cthat
        these terrible things you\u2019ve said won\u2019t happen to me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After testifying and preaching the word of the Lord in Samaria, Peter
        and John returned to Jerusalem. And they stopped in many Samaritan villages
        along the way to preach the Good News.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Philip and the Ethiopian Eunuch
      content: "As for Philip, an angel of the Lord said to him, \u201CGo south[COMMENT[0]]
        down the desert road that runs from Jerusalem to Gaza.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '8:26 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Go at noon.
    - title: 
      content: 'So he started out, and he met the treasurer of Ethiopia, a eunuch
        of great authority under the Kandake, the queen of Ethiopia. The eunuch had
        gone to Jerusalem to worship, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he was now returning. Seated in his carriage, he was reading
        aloud from the book of the prophet Isaiah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Holy Spirit said to Philip, \u201CGo over and walk along beside
        the carriage.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Philip ran over and heard the man reading from the prophet Isaiah.
        Philip asked, \u201CDo you understand what you are reading?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The man replied, \u201CHow can I, unless someone instructs me?\u201D
        And he urged Philip to come up into the carriage and sit with him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The passage of Scripture he had been reading was this:\n\t\u201CHe
        was led like a sheep to the slaughter.\n\tAnd as a lamb is silent before
        the shearers,\n\the did not open his mouth.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He was humiliated and received no justice.\n\tWho can speak of his
        descendants?\n\tFor his life was taken from the earth.\u201D[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:32-33 '
        contents:
        - ft: Isa 53:7-8 (Greek version).
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "The eunuch asked Philip, \u201CTell me, was the prophet talking about
        himself or someone else?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So beginning with this same Scripture, Philip told him the Good News
        about Jesus.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As they rode along, they came to some water, and the eunuch said,
        \u201CLook! There\u2019s some water! Why can\u2019t I be baptized?\u201D[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:36 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts add verse 37, '
          body: "\u201CYou can,\u201D Philip answered, \u201Cif you believe with
            all your heart.\u201D And the eunuch replied, \u201CI believe that Jesus
            Christ is the Son of God.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'He ordered the carriage to stop, and they went down into the water,
        and Philip baptized him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they came up out of the water, the Spirit of the Lord snatched
        Philip away. The eunuch never saw him again but went on his way rejoicing. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Meanwhile, Philip found himself farther north at the town of Azotus.
        He preached the Good News there and in every town along the way until he
        came to Caesarea.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Saul\u2019s Conversion"
      content: "Meanwhile, Saul was uttering threats with every breath and was eager
        to kill the Lord\u2019s followers.[COMMENT[0]] So he went to the high priest. "
      comments:
      - number: '9:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: disciples.
    - title: 
      content: "He requested letters addressed to the synagogues in Damascus, asking
        for their cooperation in the arrest of any followers of the Way he found
        there. He wanted to bring them\u2014both men and women\u2014back to Jerusalem
        in chains.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As he was approaching Damascus on this mission, a light from heaven
        suddenly shone down around him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He fell to the ground and heard a voice saying to him, \n\t\u201CSaul!
        Saul! Why are you persecuting me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWho are you, lord?\u201D Saul asked.\n\tAnd the voice replied,
        \n\t\u201CI am Jesus, the one you are persecuting!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now get up and go into the city, and you will be told what you must
        do.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The men with Saul stood speechless, for they heard the sound of someone\u2019s
        voice but saw no one! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Saul picked himself up off the ground, but when he opened his eyes
        he was blind. So his companions led him by the hand to Damascus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He remained there blind for three days and did not eat or drink.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now there was a believer[COMMENT[0]] in Damascus named Ananias. The
        Lord spoke to him in a vision, calling, \n\t\u201CAnanias!\u201D\n\t\u201CYes,
        Lord!\u201D he replied.  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'disciple; '
        - ft: also in 9:26, 36.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "The Lord said, \n\t\u201CGo over to Straight Street, to the house
        of Judas. When you get there, ask for a man from Tarsus named Saul. He is
        praying to me right now.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have shown him a vision of a man named Ananias coming in and laying
        hands on him so he can see again.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut Lord,\u201D exclaimed Ananias, \u201CI\u2019ve heard many
        people talk about the terrible things this man has done to the believers[COMMENT[0]]
        in Jerusalem! "
      comments:
      - number: '9:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: "God\u2019s holy people; "
        - ft: also in 9:32, 41.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "And he is authorized by the leading priests to arrest everyone who
        calls upon your name.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the Lord said, \n\t\u201CGo, for Saul is my chosen instrument
        to take my message to the Gentiles and to kings, as well as to the people
        of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I will show him how much he must suffer for my name\u2019s sake.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Ananias went and found Saul. He laid his hands on him and said,
        \u201CBrother Saul, the Lord Jesus, who appeared to you on the road, has
        sent me so that you might regain your sight and be filled with the Holy Spirit.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Instantly something like scales fell from Saul\u2019s eyes, and he
        regained his sight. Then he got up and was baptized. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Afterward he ate some food and regained his strength.Saul stayed
        with the believers[COMMENT[0]] in Damascus for a few days. '
      comments:
      - number: '9:19 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'disciples; '
        - ft: also in 9:26, 38.
          body: 
    - title: Saul in Damascus and Jerusalem
      content: "And immediately he began preaching about Jesus in the synagogues,
        saying, \u201CHe is indeed the Son of God!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All who heard him were amazed. \u201CIsn\u2019t this the same man
        who caused such devastation among Jesus\u2019 followers in Jerusalem?\u201D
        they asked. \u201CAnd didn\u2019t he come here to arrest them and take them
        in chains to the leading priests?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul\u2019s preaching became more and more powerful, and the Jews
        in Damascus couldn\u2019t refute his proofs that Jesus was indeed the Messiah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After a while some of the Jews plotted together to kill him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They were watching for him day and night at the city gate so they
        could murder him, but Saul was told about their plot. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So during the night, some of the other believers[COMMENT[0]] lowered
        him in a large basket through an opening in the city wall.  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:25 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: his disciples.
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul arrived in Jerusalem, he tried to meet with the believers,
        but they were all afraid of him. They did not believe he had truly become
        a believer! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Barnabas brought him to the apostles and told them how Saul
        had seen the Lord on the way to Damascus and how the Lord had spoken to Saul.
        He also told them that Saul had preached boldly in the name of Jesus in Damascus.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Saul stayed with the apostles and went all around Jerusalem with
        them, preaching boldly in the name of the Lord. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He debated with some Greek-speaking Jews, but they tried to murder
        him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the believers[COMMENT[0]] heard about this, they took him down
        to Caesarea and sent him away to Tarsus, his hometown.  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:30 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: brothers.
    - title: 
      content: 'The church then had peace throughout Judea, Galilee, and Samaria,
        and it became stronger as the believers lived in the fear of the Lord. And
        with the encouragement of the Holy Spirit, it also grew in numbers.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Peter Heals Aeneas and Raises Dorcas
      content: 'Meanwhile, Peter traveled from place to place, and he came down to
        visit the believers in the town of Lydda. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There he met a man named Aeneas, who had been paralyzed and bedridden
        for eight years. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter said to him, \u201CAeneas, Jesus Christ heals you! Get up,
        and roll up your sleeping mat!\u201D And he was healed instantly. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the whole population of Lydda and Sharon saw Aeneas walking
        around, and they turned to the Lord.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There was a believer in Joppa named Tabitha (which in Greek is Dorcas[COMMENT[0]]).
        She was always doing kind things for others and helping the poor. '
      comments:
      - number: '9:36 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'The names '
          body: 'Tabitha '
        - ft: 'in Aramaic and '
          body: 'Dorcas '
        - ft: "in Greek both mean \u201Cgazelle.\u201D"
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'About this time she became ill and died. Her body was washed for
        burial and laid in an upstairs room. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the believers had heard that Peter was nearby at Lydda, so they
        sent two men to beg him, \u201CPlease come as soon as possible!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Peter returned with them; and as soon as he arrived, they took
        him to the upstairs room. The room was filled with widows who were weeping
        and showing him the coats and other clothes Dorcas had made for them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Peter asked them all to leave the room; then he knelt and prayed.
        Turning to the body he said, \u201CGet up, Tabitha.\u201D And she opened
        her eyes! When she saw Peter, she sat up! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He gave her his hand and helped her up. Then he called in the widows
        and all the believers, and he presented her to them alive.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The news spread through the whole town, and many believed in the
        Lord. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: And Peter stayed a long time in Joppa, living with Simon, a tanner
        of hides.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Cornelius Calls for Peter
      content: 'In Caesarea there lived a Roman army officer[COMMENT[0]] named Cornelius,
        who was a captain of the Italian Regiment. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'a centurion; '
        - ft: similarly in 10:22.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'He was a devout, God-fearing man, as was everyone in his household.
        He gave generously to the poor and prayed regularly to God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One afternoon about three o\u2019clock, he had a vision in which
        he saw an angel of God coming toward him. \u201CCornelius!\u201D the angel
        said.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Cornelius stared at him in terror. \u201CWhat is it, sir?\u201D he
        asked the angel.\n\tAnd the angel replied, \u201CYour prayers and gifts to
        the poor have been received by God as an offering! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now send some men to Joppa, and summon a man named Simon Peter. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He is staying with Simon, a tanner who lives near the seashore.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as the angel was gone, Cornelius called two of his household
        servants and a devout soldier, one of his personal attendants. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He told them what had happened and sent them off to Joppa.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Peter Visits Cornelius
      content: "The next day as Cornelius\u2019s messengers were nearing the town,
        Peter went up on the flat roof to pray. It was about noon, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he was hungry. But while a meal was being prepared, he fell into
        a trance. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He saw the sky open, and something like a large sheet was let down
        by its four corners. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the sheet were all sorts of animals, reptiles, and birds. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then a voice said to him, \u201CGet up, Peter; kill and eat them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo, Lord,\u201D Peter declared. \u201CI have never eaten anything
        that our Jewish laws have declared impure and unclean.[COMMENT[0]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: anything common and unclean.
    - title: 
      content: "But the voice spoke again: \u201CDo not call something unclean if
        God has made it clean.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The same vision was repeated three times. Then the sheet was suddenly
        pulled up to heaven.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter was very perplexed. What could the vision mean? Just then the
        men sent by Cornelius found Simon\u2019s house. Standing outside the gate, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'they asked if a man named Simon Peter was staying there.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, as Peter was puzzling over the vision, the Holy Spirit
        said to him, \u201CThree men have come looking for you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Get up, go downstairs, and go with them without hesitation. Don\u2019t
        worry, for I have sent them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Peter went down and said, \u201CI\u2019m the man you are looking
        for. Why have you come?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They said, \u201CWe were sent by Cornelius, a Roman officer. He is
        a devout and God-fearing man, well respected by all the Jews. A holy angel
        instructed him to summon you to his house so that he can hear your message.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Peter invited the men to stay for the night. The next day he went
        with them, accompanied by some of the brothers from Joppa.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They arrived in Caesarea the following day. Cornelius was waiting
        for them and had called together his relatives and close friends. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As Peter entered his home, Cornelius fell at his feet and worshiped
        him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Peter pulled him up and said, \u201CStand up! I\u2019m a human
        being just like you!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they talked together and went inside, where many others were assembled.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter told them, \u201CYou know it is against our laws for a Jewish
        man to enter a Gentile home like this or to associate with you. But God has
        shown me that I should no longer think of anyone as impure or unclean. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I came without objection as soon as I was sent for. Now tell me
        why you sent for me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Cornelius replied, \u201CFour days ago I was praying in my house
        about this same time, three o\u2019clock in the afternoon. Suddenly, a man
        in dazzling clothes was standing in front of me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He told me, \u2018Cornelius, your prayer has been heard, and your
        gifts to the poor have been noticed by God! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now send messengers to Joppa, and summon a man named Simon Peter.
        He is staying in the home of Simon, a tanner who lives near the seashore.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I sent for you at once, and it was good of you to come. Now we
        are all here, waiting before God to hear the message the Lord has given you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Gentiles Hear the Good News
      content: "Then Peter replied, \u201CI see very clearly that God shows no favoritism. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In every nation he accepts those who fear him and do what is right. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is the message of Good News for the people of Israel\u2014that
        there is peace with God through Jesus Christ, who is Lord of all. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You know what happened throughout Judea, beginning in Galilee, after
        John began preaching his message of baptism. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And you know that God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit
        and with power. Then Jesus went around doing good and healing all who were
        oppressed by the devil, for God was with him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd we apostles are witnesses of all he did throughout Judea
        and in Jerusalem. They put him to death by hanging him on a cross,[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:39 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: on a tree.
    - title: 
      content: 'but God raised him to life on the third day. Then God allowed him
        to appear, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'not to the general public,[COMMENT[0]] but to us whom God had chosen
        in advance to be his witnesses. We were those who ate and drank with him
        after he rose from the dead. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:41 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the people.
    - title: 
      content: "And he ordered us to preach everywhere and to testify that Jesus
        is the one appointed by God to be the judge of all\u2014the living and the
        dead. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He is the one all the prophets testified about, saying that everyone
        who believes in him will have their sins forgiven through his name.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Gentiles Receive the Holy Spirit
      content: 'Even as Peter was saying these things, the Holy Spirit fell upon
        all who were listening to the message. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Jewish believers[COMMENT[0]] who came with Peter were amazed
        that the gift of the Holy Spirit had been poured out on the Gentiles, too. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:45 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: The faithful ones of the circumcision.
    - title: 
      content: "For they heard them speaking in other tongues[COMMENT[0]] and praising
        God.\n\tThen Peter asked, "
      comments:
      - number: '10:46 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: in other languages.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCan anyone object to their being baptized, now that they have
        received the Holy Spirit just as we did?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: So he gave orders for them to be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ.
        Afterward Cornelius asked him to stay with them for several days.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Peter Explains His Actions
      content: 'Soon the news reached the apostles and other believers[COMMENT[0]]
        in Judea that the Gentiles had received the word of God. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: brothers.
    - title: 
      content: 'But when Peter arrived back in Jerusalem, the Jewish believers[COMMENT[0]]
        criticized him. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: those of the circumcision.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou entered the home of Gentiles[COMMENT[0]] and even ate with
        them!\u201D they said.  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:3 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: of uncircumcised men.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Peter told them exactly what had happened. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI was in the town of Joppa,\u201D he said, \u201Cand while
        I was praying, I went into a trance and saw a vision. Something like a large
        sheet was let down by its four corners from the sky. And it came right down
        to me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I looked inside the sheet, I saw all sorts of tame and wild
        animals, reptiles, and birds. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I heard a voice say, \u2018Get up, Peter; kill and eat them.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201C\u2018No, Lord,\u2019 I replied. \u2018I have never eaten anything
        that our Jewish laws have declared impure or unclean.[COMMENT[0]]\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:8 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: anything common or unclean.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut the voice from heaven spoke again: \u2018Do not call something
        unclean if God has made it clean.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This happened three times before the sheet and all it contained was
        pulled back up to heaven.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CJust then three men who had been sent from Caesarea arrived
        at the house where we were staying. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Holy Spirit told me to go with them and not to worry that they
        were Gentiles. These six brothers here accompanied me, and we soon entered
        the home of the man who had sent for us. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He told us how an angel had appeared to him in his home and had told
        him, \u2018Send messengers to Joppa, and summon a man named Simon Peter. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He will tell you how you and everyone in your household can be saved!\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAs I began to speak,\u201D Peter continued, \u201Cthe Holy
        Spirit fell on them, just as he fell on us at the beginning. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I thought of the Lord\u2019s words when he said, \n\t\u2018John
        baptized with[COMMENT[0]]  \n\twater, but you will be baptized with the Holy
        Spirit.\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'in; '
        - ft: also in 11:16b.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "And since God gave these Gentiles the same gift he gave us when we
        believed in the Lord Jesus Christ, who was I to stand in God\u2019s way?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the others heard this, they stopped objecting and began praising
        God. They said, \u201CWe can see that God has also given the Gentiles the
        privilege of repenting of their sins and receiving eternal life.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Church in Antioch of Syria
      content: "Meanwhile, the believers who had been scattered during the persecution
        after Stephen\u2019s death traveled as far as Phoenicia, Cyprus, and Antioch
        of Syria. They preached the word of God, but only to Jews. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'However, some of the believers who went to Antioch from Cyprus and
        Cyrene began preaching to the Gentiles[COMMENT[0]] about the Lord Jesus. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:20 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'the Hellenists '
        - ft: '(i.e., those who speak Greek); other manuscripts read '
          body: the Greeks.
    - title: 
      content: 'The power of the Lord was with them, and a large number of these
        Gentiles believed and turned to the Lord.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the church at Jerusalem heard what had happened, they sent Barnabas
        to Antioch. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When he arrived and saw this evidence of God\u2019s blessing, he
        was filled with joy, and he encouraged the believers to stay true to the
        Lord. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Barnabas was a good man, full of the Holy Spirit and strong in faith.
        And many people were brought to the Lord.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Barnabas went on to Tarsus to look for Saul. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When he found him, he brought him back to Antioch. Both of them stayed
        there with the church for a full year, teaching large crowds of people. (It
        was at Antioch that the believers[COMMENT[0]] were first called Christians.)  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:26 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'disciples; '
        - ft: also in 11:29.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'During this time some prophets traveled from Jerusalem to Antioch. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One of them named Agabus stood up in one of the meetings and predicted
        by the Spirit that a great famine was coming upon the entire Roman world.
        (This was fulfilled during the reign of Claudius.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the believers in Antioch decided to send relief to the brothers
        and sisters[COMMENT[0]] in Judea, everyone giving as much as they could. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:29 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the brothers.
    - title: 
      content: This they did, entrusting their gifts to Barnabas and Saul to take
        to the elders of the church in Jerusalem.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: James Is Killed and Peter Is Imprisoned
      content: 'About that time King Herod Agrippa[COMMENT[0]] began to persecute
        some believers in the church. '
      comments:
      - number: '12:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'Herod the king. '
        - ft: He was the nephew of Herod Antipas and a grandson of Herod the Great.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "He had the apostle James (John\u2019s brother) killed with a sword. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Herod saw how much this pleased the Jewish people, he also arrested
        Peter. (This took place during the Passover celebration.[COMMENT[0]]) '
      comments:
      - number: '12:3 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the days of unleavened bread.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he imprisoned him, placing him under the guard of four squads
        of four soldiers each. Herod intended to bring Peter out for public trial
        after the Passover. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But while Peter was in prison, the church prayed very earnestly for
        him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: "Peter\u2019s Miraculous Escape from Prison"
      content: 'The night before Peter was to be placed on trial, he was asleep,
        fastened with two chains between two soldiers. Others stood guard at the
        prison gate. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Suddenly, there was a bright light in the cell, and an angel of the
        Lord stood before Peter. The angel struck him on the side to awaken him and
        said, \u201CQuick! Get up!\u201D And the chains fell off his wrists. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the angel told him, \u201CGet dressed and put on your sandals.\u201D
        And he did. \u201CNow put on your coat and follow me,\u201D the angel ordered.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Peter left the cell, following the angel. But all the time he
        thought it was a vision. He didn\u2019t realize it was actually happening. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They passed the first and second guard posts and came to the iron
        gate leading to the city, and this opened for them all by itself. So they
        passed through and started walking down the street, and then the angel suddenly
        left him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Peter finally came to his senses. \u201CIt\u2019s really true!\u201D
        he said. \u201CThe Lord has sent his angel and saved me from Herod and from
        what the Jewish leaders[COMMENT[0]] had planned to do to me!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '12:11 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: the Jewish people.
    - title: 
      content: 'When he realized this, he went to the home of Mary, the mother of
        John Mark, where many were gathered for prayer. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He knocked at the door in the gate, and a servant girl named Rhoda
        came to open it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When she recognized Peter\u2019s voice, she was so overjoyed that,
        instead of opening the door, she ran back inside and told everyone, \u201CPeter
        is standing at the door!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou\u2019re out of your mind!\u201D they said. When she insisted,
        they decided, \u201CIt must be his angel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, Peter continued knocking. When they finally opened the
        door and saw him, they were amazed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He motioned for them to quiet down and told them how the Lord had
        led him out of prison. \u201CTell James and the other brothers what happened,\u201D
        he said. And then he went to another place.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At dawn there was a great commotion among the soldiers about what
        had happened to Peter. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Herod Agrippa ordered a thorough search for him. When he couldn\u2019t
        be found, Herod interrogated the guards and sentenced them to death. Afterward
        Herod left Judea to stay in Caesarea for a while.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Death of Herod Agrippa
      content: "Now Herod was very angry with the people of Tyre and Sidon. So they
        sent a delegation to make peace with him because their cities were dependent
        upon Herod\u2019s country for food. The delegates won the support of Blastus,
        Herod\u2019s personal assistant, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and an appointment with Herod was granted. When the day arrived,
        Herod put on his royal robes, sat on his throne, and made a speech to them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people gave him a great ovation, shouting, \u201CIt\u2019s the
        voice of a god, not of a man!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Instantly, an angel of the Lord struck Herod with a sickness, because
        he accepted the people\u2019s worship instead of giving the glory to God.
        So he was consumed with worms and died.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, the word of God continued to spread, and there were many
        new believers.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: When Barnabas and Saul had finished their mission to Jerusalem, they
        returned,[COMMENT[0]] taking John Mark with them.
      comments:
      - number: '12:25 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'mission, they returned to Jerusalem. '
        - ft: 'Other manuscripts read '
          body: 'mission, they returned from Jerusalem; '
        - ft: 'still others read '
          body: mission, they returned from Jerusalem to Antioch.
  - verses:
    - title: Barnabas and Saul Are Commissioned
      content: "Among the prophets and teachers of the church at Antioch of Syria
        were Barnabas, Simeon (called \u201Cthe black man\u201D[COMMENT[0]]), Lucius
        (from Cyrene), Manaen (the childhood companion of King Herod Antipas[COMMENT[1]]),
        and Saul. "
      comments:
      - number: '13:1a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: who was called Niger.
      - number: '13:1b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Herod the tetrarch.
    - title: 
      content: "One day as these men were worshiping the Lord and fasting, the Holy
        Spirit said, \u201CAppoint Barnabas and Saul for the special work to which
        I have called them.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So after more fasting and prayer, the men laid their hands on them
        and sent them on their way.  '
      comments: []
    - title: "Paul\u2019s First Missionary Journey"
      content: 'So Barnabas and Saul were sent out by the Holy Spirit. They went
        down to the seaport of Seleucia and then sailed for the island of Cyprus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There, in the town of Salamis, they went to the Jewish synagogues
        and preached the word of God. John Mark went with them as their assistant.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Afterward they traveled from town to town across the entire island
        until finally they reached Paphos, where they met a Jewish sorcerer, a false
        prophet named Bar-Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He had attached himself to the governor, Sergius Paulus, who was
        an intelligent man. The governor invited Barnabas and Saul to visit him,
        for he wanted to hear the word of God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Elymas, the sorcerer (as his name means in Greek), interfered
        and urged the governor to pay no attention to what Barnabas and Saul said.
        He was trying to keep the governor from believing.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Saul, also known as Paul, was filled with the Holy Spirit, and he
        looked the sorcerer in the eye. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said, \u201CYou son of the devil, full of every sort of deceit
        and fraud, and enemy of all that is good! Will you never stop perverting
        the true ways of the Lord? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Watch now, for the Lord has laid his hand of punishment upon you,
        and you will be struck blind. You will not see the sunlight for some time.\u201D
        Instantly mist and darkness came over the man\u2019s eyes, and he began groping
        around begging for someone to take his hand and lead him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the governor saw what had happened, he became a believer, for
        he was astonished at the teaching about the Lord.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Preaches in Antioch of Pisidia
      content: 'Paul and his companions then left Paphos by ship for Pamphylia, landing
        at the port town of Perga. There John Mark left them and returned to Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Paul and Barnabas traveled inland to Antioch of Pisidia.[COMMENT[0]]On
        the Sabbath they went to the synagogue for the services. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:13-14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Pamphylia '
        - ft: 'and '
          body: 'Pisidia '
        - ft: were districts in what is now Turkey.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "After the usual readings from the books of Moses[COMMENT[0]] and
        the prophets, those in charge of the service sent them this message: \u201CBrothers,
        if you have any word of encouragement for the people, come and give it.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: from the law.
    - title: 
      content: "So Paul stood, lifted his hand to quiet them, and started speaking.
        \u201CMen of Israel,\u201D he said, \u201Cand you God-fearing Gentiles, listen
        to me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe God of this nation of Israel chose our ancestors and made
        them multiply and grow strong during their stay in Egypt. Then with a powerful
        arm he led them out of their slavery. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He put up with them[COMMENT[0]] through forty years of wandering
        in the wilderness. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:18 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: 'He cared for them; '
        - ft: compare Deut 1:31.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he destroyed seven nations in Canaan and gave their land to
        Israel as an inheritance. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All this took about 450 years.\n\t\u201CAfter that, God gave them
        judges to rule until the time of Samuel the prophet. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the people begged for a king, and God gave them Saul son of
        Kish, a man of the tribe of Benjamin, who reigned for forty years. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But God removed Saul and replaced him with David, a man about whom
        God said, \u2018I have found David son of Jesse, a man after my own heart.
        He will do everything I want him to do.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 1 Sam 13:14.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd it is one of King David\u2019s descendants, Jesus, who
        is God\u2019s promised Savior of Israel! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Before he came, John the Baptist preached that all the people of
        Israel needed to repent of their sins and turn to God and be baptized. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As John was finishing his ministry he asked, \u2018Do you think I
        am the Messiah? No, I am not! But he is coming soon\u2014and I\u2019m not
        even worthy to be his slave and untie the sandals on his feet.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBrothers\u2014you sons of Abraham, and also you God-fearing
        Gentiles\u2014this message of salvation has been sent to us! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people in Jerusalem and their leaders did not recognize Jesus
        as the one the prophets had spoken about. Instead, they condemned him, and
        in doing this they fulfilled the prophets\u2019 words that are read every
        Sabbath. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They found no legal reason to execute him, but they asked Pilate
        to have him killed anyway.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen they had done all that the prophecies said about him,
        they took him down from the cross[COMMENT[0]] and placed him in a tomb. "
      comments:
      - number: '13:29 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: from the tree.
    - title: 
      content: 'But God raised him from the dead! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And over a period of many days he appeared to those who had gone
        with him from Galilee to Jerusalem. They are now his witnesses to the people
        of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd now we are here to bring you this Good News. The promise
        was made to our ancestors, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and God has now fulfilled it for us, their descendants, by raising
        Jesus. This is what the second psalm says about Jesus:\n\t\u2018You are my
        Son.\n\tToday I have become your Father.[COMMENT[0]]\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:33 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'Today I reveal you as my Son. '
        - ft: Ps 2:7.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "For God had promised to raise him from the dead, not leaving him
        to rot in the grave. He said, \u2018I will give you the sacred blessings
        I promised to David.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:34 '
        contents:
        - ft: Isa 55:3.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Another psalm explains it more fully: \u2018You will not allow your
        Holy One to rot in the grave.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:35 '
        contents:
        - ft: Ps 16:10.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'This is not a reference to David, for after David had done the will
        of God in his own generation, he died and was buried with his ancestors,
        and his body decayed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No, it was a reference to someone else\u2014someone whom God raised
        and whose body did not decay.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "  [COMMENT[1]]\u201CBrothers, listen! We are here to proclaim that
        through this man Jesus there is forgiveness for your sins. "
      comments:
      - number: 
        contents:
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
      - number: '13:38 '
        contents:
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
        - ft: English translations divide verses 38 and 39 in various ways.
          body: 
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Everyone who believes in him is made right in God\u2019s sight\u2014something
        the law of Moses could never do. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Be careful! Don\u2019t let the prophets\u2019 words apply to you.
        For they said,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Look, you mockers,\n\tbe amazed and die!\n\tFor I am doing
        something in your own day,\n\tsomething you wouldn\u2019t believe\n\teven
        if someone told you about it.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:41 '
        contents:
        - ft: Hab 1:5 (Greek version).
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'As Paul and Barnabas left the synagogue that day, the people begged
        them to speak about these things again the next week. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Many Jews and devout converts to Judaism followed Paul and Barnabas,
        and the two men urged them to continue to rely on the grace of God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Turns to the Gentiles
      content: 'The following week almost the entire city turned out to hear them
        preach the word of the Lord. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when some of the Jews saw the crowds, they were jealous; so they
        slandered Paul and argued against whatever he said.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Paul and Barnabas spoke out boldly and declared, \u201CIt was
        necessary that we first preach the word of God to you Jews. But since you
        have rejected it and judged yourselves unworthy of eternal life, we will
        offer it to the Gentiles. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the Lord gave us this command when he said,\n\t\u2018I have made
        you a light to the Gentiles,\n\tto bring salvation to the farthest corners
        of the earth.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:47 '
        contents:
        - ft: Isa 49:6.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'When the Gentiles heard this, they were very glad and thanked the
        Lord for his message; and all who were chosen for eternal life became believers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the Lord\u2019s message spread throughout that region.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the Jews stirred up the influential religious women and the
        leaders of the city, and they incited a mob against Paul and Barnabas and
        ran them out of town. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they shook the dust from their feet as a sign of rejection and
        went to the town of Iconium. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: And the believers[COMMENT[0]] were filled with joy and with the Holy
        Spirit.
      comments:
      - number: '13:52 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the disciples.
  - verses:
    - title: Paul and Barnabas in Iconium
      content: 'The same thing happened in Iconium.[COMMENT[0]] Paul and Barnabas
        went to the Jewish synagogue and preached with such power that a great number
        of both Jews and Greeks became believers. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Iconium, '
        - ft: 'as well as '
          body: 'Lystra '
        - ft: 'and '
          body: 'Derbe '
        - ft: (14:6), were towns in what is now Turkey.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Some of the Jews, however, spurned God\u2019s message and poisoned
        the minds of the Gentiles against Paul and Barnabas. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the apostles stayed there a long time, preaching boldly about
        the grace of the Lord. And the Lord proved their message was true by giving
        them power to do miraculous signs and wonders. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the people of the town were divided in their opinion about them.
        Some sided with the Jews, and some with the apostles.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then a mob of Gentiles and Jews, along with their leaders, decided
        to attack and stone them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the apostles learned of it, they fled to the region of Lycaonia\u2014to
        the towns of Lystra and Derbe and the surrounding area. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And there they preached the Good News.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul and Barnabas in Lystra and Derbe
      content: 'While they were at Lystra, Paul and Barnabas came upon a man with
        crippled feet. He had been that way from birth, so he had never walked. He
        was sitting '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and listening as Paul preached. Looking straight at him, Paul realized
        he had faith to be healed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Paul called to him in a loud voice, \u201CStand up!\u201D And
        the man jumped to his feet and started walking.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the crowd saw what Paul had done, they shouted in their local
        dialect, \u201CThese men are gods in human form!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They decided that Barnabas was the Greek god Zeus and that Paul was
        Hermes, since he was the chief speaker. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now the temple of Zeus was located just outside the town. So the
        priest of the temple and the crowd brought bulls and wreaths of flowers to
        the town gates, and they prepared to offer sacrifices to the apostles.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard what was happening,
        they tore their clothing in dismay and ran out among the people, shouting, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFriends,[COMMENT[0]] why are you doing this? We are merely
        human beings\u2014just like you! We have come to bring you the Good News
        that you should turn from these worthless things and turn to the living God,
        who made heaven and earth, the sea, and everything in them. "
      comments:
      - number: '14:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Men.
    - title: 
      content: 'In the past he permitted all the nations to go their own ways, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "but he never left them without evidence of himself and his goodness.
        For instance, he sends you rain and good crops and gives you food and joyful
        hearts.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But even with these words, Paul and Barnabas could scarcely restrain
        the people from sacrificing to them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then some Jews arrived from Antioch and Iconium and won the crowds
        to their side. They stoned Paul and dragged him out of town, thinking he
        was dead. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But as the believers[COMMENT[0]] gathered around him, he got up and
        went back into the town. The next day he left with Barnabas for Derbe.  '
      comments:
      - number: '14:20 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'disciples; '
        - ft: also in 14:22, 28.
          body: 
    - title: Paul and Barnabas Return to Antioch of Syria
      content: 'After preaching the Good News in Derbe and making many disciples,
        Paul and Barnabas returned to Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch of Pisidia, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'where they strengthened the believers. They encouraged them to continue
        in the faith, reminding them that we must suffer many hardships to enter
        the Kingdom of God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Paul and Barnabas also appointed elders in every church. With prayer
        and fasting, they turned the elders over to the care of the Lord, in whom
        they had put their trust. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they traveled back through Pisidia to Pamphylia. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They preached the word in Perga, then went down to Attalia.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Finally, they returned by ship to Antioch of Syria, where their journey
        had begun. The believers there had entrusted them to the grace of God to
        do the work they had now completed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Upon arriving in Antioch, they called the church together and reported
        everything God had done through them and how he had opened the door of faith
        to the Gentiles, too. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: And they stayed there with the believers for a long time.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Council at Jerusalem
      content: "While Paul and Barnabas were at Antioch of Syria, some men from Judea
        arrived and began to teach the believers[COMMENT[0]]: \u201CUnless you are
        circumcised as required by the law of Moses, you cannot be saved.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '15:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'brothers; '
        - ft: also in 15:3, 23, 32, 33, 36, 40.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Paul and Barnabas disagreed with them, arguing vehemently. Finally,
        the church decided to send Paul and Barnabas to Jerusalem, accompanied by
        some local believers, to talk to the apostles and elders about this question. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The church sent the delegates to Jerusalem, and they stopped along
        the way in Phoenicia and Samaria to visit the believers. They told them\u2014much
        to everyone\u2019s joy\u2014that the Gentiles, too, were being converted.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they arrived in Jerusalem, Barnabas and Paul were welcomed by
        the whole church, including the apostles and elders. They reported everything
        God had done through them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But then some of the believers who belonged to the sect of the Pharisees
        stood up and insisted, \u201CThe Gentile converts must be circumcised and
        required to follow the law of Moses.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the apostles and elders met together to resolve this issue. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At the meeting, after a long discussion, Peter stood and addressed
        them as follows: \u201CBrothers, you all know that God chose me from among
        you some time ago to preach to the Gentiles so that they could hear the Good
        News and believe. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God knows people\u2019s hearts, and he confirmed that he accepts
        Gentiles by giving them the Holy Spirit, just as he did to us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made no distinction between us and them, for he cleansed their
        hearts through faith. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So why are you now challenging God by burdening the Gentile believers[COMMENT[0]]
        with a yoke that neither we nor our ancestors were able to bear? '
      comments:
      - number: '15:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: disciples.
    - title: 
      content: "We believe that we are all saved the same way, by the undeserved
        grace of the Lord Jesus.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Everyone listened quietly as Barnabas and Paul told about the miraculous
        signs and wonders God had done through them among the Gentiles.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they had finished, James stood and said, \u201CBrothers, listen
        to me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Peter[COMMENT[0]] has told you about the time God first visited the
        Gentiles to take from them a people for himself. '
      comments:
      - number: '15:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Simeon.
    - title: 
      content: 'And this conversion of Gentiles is exactly what the prophets predicted.
        As it is written:  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Afterward I will return\n\tand restore the fallen house[COMMENT[0]]
        of David.\n\tI will rebuild its ruins\n\tand restore it,  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'kingdom; '
        - ft: 'Greek reads '
          body: tent.
    - title: 
      content: "so that the rest of humanity might seek the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t,\n\tincluding
        the Gentiles\u2014\n\tall those I have called to be mine.\n\tThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has spoken\u2014  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he who made these things known so long ago.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:16-18 '
        contents:
        - ft: Amos 9:11-12 (Greek version); Isa 45:21.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd so my judgment is that we should not make it difficult
        for the Gentiles who are turning to God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Instead, we should write and tell them to abstain from eating food
        offered to idols, from sexual immorality, from eating the meat of strangled
        animals, and from consuming blood. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For these laws of Moses have been preached in Jewish synagogues in
        every city on every Sabbath for many generations.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Letter for Gentile Believers
      content: "Then the apostles and elders together with the whole church in Jerusalem
        chose delegates, and they sent them to Antioch of Syria with Paul and Barnabas
        to report on this decision. The men chosen were two of the church leaders[COMMENT[0]]\u2014Judas
        (also called Barsabbas) and Silas. "
      comments:
      - number: '15:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: were leaders among the brothers.
    - title: 
      content: "This is the letter they took with them:\n\t\u201CThis letter is from
        the apostles and elders, your brothers in Jerusalem. It is written to the
        Gentile believers in Antioch, Syria, and Cilicia. Greetings!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe understand that some men from here have troubled you and
        upset you with their teaching, but we did not send them! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So we decided, having come to complete agreement, to send you official
        representatives, along with our beloved Barnabas and Paul, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'who have risked their lives for the name of our Lord Jesus Christ. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We are sending Judas and Silas to confirm what we have decided concerning
        your question.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor it seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us to lay no greater
        burden on you than these few requirements: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You must abstain from eating food offered to idols, from consuming
        blood or the meat of strangled animals, and from sexual immorality. If you
        do this, you will do well. Farewell.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The messengers went at once to Antioch, where they called a general
        meeting of the believers and delivered the letter. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And there was great joy throughout the church that day as they read
        this encouraging message.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Judas and Silas, both being prophets, spoke at length to the
        believers, encouraging and strengthening their faith. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They stayed for a while, and then the believers sent them back to
        the church in Jerusalem with a blessing of peace.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:33 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts add verse 34, '
          body: But Silas decided to stay there.
    - title: 
      content: 'Paul and Barnabas stayed in Antioch. They and many others taught
        and preached the word of the Lord there.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul and Barnabas Separate
      content: "After some time Paul said to Barnabas, \u201CLet\u2019s go back and
        visit each city where we previously preached the word of the Lord, to see
        how the new believers are doing.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Barnabas agreed and wanted to take along John Mark. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Paul disagreed strongly, since John Mark had deserted them in
        Pamphylia and had not continued with them in their work. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Their disagreement was so sharp that they separated. Barnabas took
        John Mark with him and sailed for Cyprus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Paul chose Silas, and as he left, the believers entrusted him to
        the Lord\u2019s gracious care. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Then he traveled throughout Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches
        there.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Paul\u2019s Second Missionary Journey"
      content: 'Paul went first to Derbe and then to Lystra, where there was a young
        disciple named Timothy. His mother was a Jewish believer, but his father
        was a Greek. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Timothy was well thought of by the believers[COMMENT[0]] in Lystra
        and Iconium, '
      comments:
      - number: '16:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'brothers; '
        - ft: also in 16:40.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'so Paul wanted him to join them on their journey. In deference to
        the Jews of the area, he arranged for Timothy to be circumcised before they
        left, for everyone knew that his father was a Greek. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they went from town to town, instructing the believers to follow
        the decisions made by the apostles and elders in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the churches were strengthened in their faith and grew larger
        every day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: A Call from Macedonia
      content: 'Next Paul and Silas traveled through the area of Phrygia and Galatia,
        because the Holy Spirit had prevented them from preaching the word in the
        province of Asia at that time. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then coming to the borders of Mysia, they headed north for the province
        of Bithynia,[COMMENT[0]] but again the Spirit of Jesus did not allow them
        to go there. '
      comments:
      - number: '16:6-7 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Phrygia, Galatia, Asia, Mysia, '
        - ft: 'and '
          body: 'Bithynia '
        - ft: were all districts in what is now Turkey.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'So instead, they went on through Mysia to the seaport of Troas.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "That night Paul had a vision: A man from Macedonia in northern Greece
        was standing there, pleading with him, \u201CCome over to Macedonia and help
        us!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So we[COMMENT[0]] decided to leave for Macedonia at once, having
        concluded that God was calling us to preach the Good News there.  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: Luke, the writer of this book, here joined Paul and accompanied him
            on his journey.
          body: 
    - title: Lydia of Philippi Believes in Jesus
      content: 'We boarded a boat at Troas and sailed straight across to the island
        of Samothrace, and the next day we landed at Neapolis. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From there we reached Philippi, a major city of that district of
        Macedonia and a Roman colony. And we stayed there several days.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the Sabbath we went a little way outside the city to a riverbank,
        where we thought people would be meeting for prayer, and we sat down to speak
        with some women who had gathered there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One of them was Lydia from Thyatira, a merchant of expensive purple
        cloth, who worshiped God. As she listened to us, the Lord opened her heart,
        and she accepted what Paul was saying. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She and her household were baptized, and she asked us to be her guests.
        \u201CIf you agree that I am a true believer in the Lord,\u201D she said,
        \u201Ccome and stay at my home.\u201D And she urged us until we agreed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Paul and Silas in Prison
      content: 'One day as we were going down to the place of prayer, we met a slave
        girl who had a spirit that enabled her to tell the future. She earned a lot
        of money for her masters by telling fortunes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She followed Paul and the rest of us, shouting, \u201CThese men are
        servants of the Most High God, and they have come to tell you how to be saved.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This went on day after day until Paul got so exasperated that he
        turned and said to the demon within her, \u201CI command you in the name
        of Jesus Christ to come out of her.\u201D And instantly it left her.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Her masters\u2019 hopes of wealth were now shattered, so they grabbed
        Paul and Silas and dragged them before the authorities at the marketplace. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe whole city is in an uproar because of these Jews!\u201D
        they shouted to the city officials. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThey are teaching customs that are illegal for us Romans to
        practice.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A mob quickly formed against Paul and Silas, and the city officials
        ordered them stripped and beaten with wooden rods. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They were severely beaten, and then they were thrown into prison.
        The jailer was ordered to make sure they didn\u2019t escape. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the jailer put them into the inner dungeon and clamped their feet
        in the stocks.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Around midnight Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to
        God, and the other prisoners were listening. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Suddenly, there was a massive earthquake, and the prison was shaken
        to its foundations. All the doors immediately flew open, and the chains of
        every prisoner fell off! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The jailer woke up to see the prison doors wide open. He assumed
        the prisoners had escaped, so he drew his sword to kill himself. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Paul shouted to him, \u201CStop! Don\u2019t kill yourself! We
        are all here!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The jailer called for lights and ran to the dungeon and fell down
        trembling before Paul and Silas. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he brought them out and asked, \u201CSirs, what must I do to
        be saved?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They replied, \u201CBelieve in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved,
        along with everyone in your household.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And they shared the word of the Lord with him and with all who lived
        in his household. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even at that hour of the night, the jailer cared for them and washed
        their wounds. Then he and everyone in his household were immediately baptized. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He brought them into his house and set a meal before them, and he
        and his entire household rejoiced because they all believed in God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The next morning the city officials sent the police to tell the jailer,
        \u201CLet those men go!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the jailer told Paul, \u201CThe city officials have said you and
        Silas are free to leave. Go in peace.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Paul replied, \u201CThey have publicly beaten us without a trial
        and put us in prison\u2014and we are Roman citizens. So now they want us
        to leave secretly? Certainly not! Let them come themselves to release us!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the police reported this, the city officials were alarmed to
        learn that Paul and Silas were Roman citizens. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they came to the jail and apologized to them. Then they brought
        them out and begged them to leave the city. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: When Paul and Silas left the prison, they returned to the home of
        Lydia. There they met with the believers and encouraged them once more. Then
        they left town.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Paul Preaches in Thessalonica
      content: 'Paul and Silas then traveled through the towns of Amphipolis and
        Apollonia and came to Thessalonica, where there was a Jewish synagogue. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As was Paul\u2019s custom, he went to the synagogue service, and
        for three Sabbaths in a row he used the Scriptures to reason with the people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He explained the prophecies and proved that the Messiah must suffer
        and rise from the dead. He said, \u201CThis Jesus I\u2019m telling you about
        is the Messiah.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some of the Jews who listened were persuaded and joined Paul and
        Silas, along with many God-fearing Greek men and quite a few prominent women.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '17:4 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: quite a few of the wives of the leading men.
    - title: 
      content: 'But some of the Jews were jealous, so they gathered some troublemakers
        from the marketplace to form a mob and start a riot. They attacked the home
        of Jason, searching for Paul and Silas so they could drag them out to the
        crowd.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '17:5 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: the city council.
    - title: 
      content: "Not finding them there, they dragged out Jason and some of the other
        believers[COMMENT[0]] instead and took them before the city council. \u201CPaul
        and Silas have caused trouble all over the world,\u201D they shouted, \u201Cand
        now they are here disturbing our city, too. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'brothers; '
        - ft: also in 17:10, 14.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "And Jason has welcomed them into his home. They are all guilty of
        treason against Caesar, for they profess allegiance to another king, named
        Jesus.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people of the city, as well as the city council, were thrown
        into turmoil by these reports. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the officials forced Jason and the other believers to post bond,
        and then they released them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul and Silas in Berea
      content: 'That very night the believers sent Paul and Silas to Berea. When
        they arrived there, they went to the Jewish synagogue. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the people of Berea were more open-minded than those in Thessalonica,
        and they listened eagerly to Paul\u2019s message. They searched the Scriptures
        day after day to see if Paul and Silas were teaching the truth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As a result, many Jews believed, as did many of the prominent Greek
        women and men.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when some Jews in Thessalonica learned that Paul was preaching
        the word of God in Berea, they went there and stirred up trouble. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The believers acted at once, sending Paul on to the coast, while
        Silas and Timothy remained behind. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Those escorting Paul went with him all the way to Athens; then they
        returned to Berea with instructions for Silas and Timothy to hurry and join
        him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Preaches in Athens
      content: 'While Paul was waiting for them in Athens, he was deeply troubled
        by all the idols he saw everywhere in the city. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He went to the synagogue to reason with the Jews and the God-fearing
        Gentiles, and he spoke daily in the public square to all who happened to
        be there.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He also had a debate with some of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophers.
        When he told them about Jesus and his resurrection, they said, \u201CWhat\u2019s
        this babbler trying to say with these strange ideas he\u2019s picked up?\u201D
        Others said, \u201CHe seems to be preaching about some foreign gods.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then they took him to the high council of the city.[COMMENT[0]] \u201CCome
        and tell us about this new teaching,\u201D they said. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:19 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'the most learned society of philosophers in the city. '
        - ft: 'Greek reads '
          body: the Areopagus.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou are saying some rather strange things, and we want to know
        what it\u2019s all about.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(It should be explained that all the Athenians as well as the foreigners
        in Athens seemed to spend all their time discussing the latest ideas.)  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Paul, standing before the council,[COMMENT[0]] addressed them
        as follows: \u201CMen of Athens, I notice that you are very religious in
        every way, "
      comments:
      - number: '17:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Traditionally rendered '
          body: 'standing in the middle of Mars Hill; '
        - ft: 'Greek reads '
          body: standing in the middle of the Areopagus.
    - title: 
      content: "for as I was walking along I saw your many shrines. And one of your
        altars had this inscription on it: \u2018To an Unknown God.\u2019 This God,
        whom you worship without knowing, is the one I\u2019m telling you about.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHe is the God who made the world and everything in it. Since
        he is Lord of heaven and earth, he doesn\u2019t live in man-made temples, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and human hands can\u2019t serve his needs\u2014for he has no needs.
        He himself gives life and breath to everything, and he satisfies every need. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From one man[COMMENT[0]] he created all the nations throughout the
        whole earth. He decided beforehand when they should rise and fall, and he
        determined their boundaries.  '
      comments:
      - number: '17:26 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'From one; '
        - ft: 'other manuscripts read '
          body: From one blood.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHis purpose was for the nations to seek after God and perhaps
        feel their way toward him and find him\u2014though he is not far from any
        one of us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For in him we live and move and exist. As some of your[COMMENT[0]]
        own poets have said, \u2018We are his offspring.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: '17:28 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: our.
    - title: 
      content: "And since this is true, we shouldn\u2019t think of God as an idol
        designed by craftsmen from gold or silver or stone.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGod overlooked people\u2019s ignorance about these things in
        earlier times, but now he commands everyone everywhere to repent of their
        sins and turn to him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For he has set a day for judging the world with justice by the man
        he has appointed, and he proved to everyone who this is by raising him from
        the dead.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they heard Paul speak about the resurrection of the dead, some
        laughed in contempt, but others said, \u201CWe want to hear more about this
        later.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "That ended Paul\u2019s discussion with them, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: but some joined him and became believers. Among them were Dionysius,
        a member of the council,[COMMENT[0]] a woman named Damaris, and others with
        them.
      comments:
      - number: '17:34 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: an Areopagite.
  - verses:
    - title: Paul Meets Priscilla and Aquila in Corinth
      content: 'Then Paul left Athens and went to Corinth.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Athens '
        - ft: 'and '
          body: 'Corinth '
        - ft: were major cities in Achaia, the region in the southern portion of
            the Greek peninsula.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'There he became acquainted with a Jew named Aquila, born in Pontus,
        who had recently arrived from Italy with his wife, Priscilla. They had left
        Italy when Claudius Caesar deported all Jews from Rome. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Paul lived and worked with them, for they were tentmakers[COMMENT[0]]
        just as he was.  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:3 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: leatherworkers.
    - title: 
      content: 'Each Sabbath found Paul at the synagogue, trying to convince the
        Jews and Greeks alike. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And after Silas and Timothy came down from Macedonia, Paul spent
        all his time preaching the word. He testified to the Jews that Jesus was
        the Messiah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when they opposed and insulted him, Paul shook the dust from
        his clothes and said, \u201CYour blood is upon your own heads\u2014I am innocent.
        From now on I will go preach to the Gentiles.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he left and went to the home of Titius Justus, a Gentile who
        worshiped God and lived next door to the synagogue. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Crispus, the leader of the synagogue, and everyone in his household
        believed in the Lord. Many others in Corinth also heard Paul, became believers,
        and were baptized.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One night the Lord spoke to Paul in a vision and told him, \n\t\u201CDon\u2019t
        be afraid! Speak out! Don\u2019t be silent!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For I am with you, and no one will attack and harm you, for many
        people in this city belong to me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Paul stayed there for the next year and a half, teaching the word
        of God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when Gallio became governor of Achaia, some Jews rose up together
        against Paul and brought him before the governor for judgment. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They accused Paul of \u201Cpersuading people to worship God in ways
        that are contrary to our law.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But just as Paul started to make his defense, Gallio turned to Paul\u2019s
        accusers and said, \u201CListen, you Jews, if this were a case involving
        some wrongdoing or a serious crime, I would have a reason to accept your
        case. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But since it is merely a question of words and names and your Jewish
        law, take care of it yourselves. I refuse to judge such matters.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And he threw them out of the courtroom.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The crowd[COMMENT[0]] then grabbed Sosthenes, the leader of the synagogue,
        and beat him right there in the courtroom. But Gallio paid no attention.  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:17 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'Everyone; '
        - ft: 'other manuscripts read '
          body: All the Greeks.
    - title: Paul Returns to Antioch of Syria
      content: 'Paul stayed in Corinth for some time after that, then said good-bye
        to the brothers and sisters[COMMENT[0]] and went to nearby Cenchrea. There
        he shaved his head according to Jewish custom, marking the end of a vow.
        Then he set sail for Syria, taking Priscilla and Aquila with him.  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:18 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'brothers; '
        - ft: also in 18:27.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'They stopped first at the port of Ephesus, where Paul left the others
        behind. While he was there, he went to the synagogue to reason with the Jews. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They asked him to stay longer, but he declined. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As he left, however, he said, \u201CI will come back later,[COMMENT[0]]
        God willing.\u201D Then he set sail from Ephesus. "
      comments:
      - number: '18:21 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: "\u201CI must by all means be at Jerusalem for the upcoming festival,
            but I will come back later.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'The next stop was at the port of Caesarea. From there he went up
        and visited the church at Jerusalem[COMMENT[0]] and then went back to Antioch.  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the church.
    - title: 
      content: 'After spending some time in Antioch, Paul went back through Galatia
        and Phrygia, visiting and strengthening all the believers.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:23 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'disciples; '
        - ft: also in 18:27.
          body: 
    - title: Apollos Instructed at Ephesus
      content: 'Meanwhile, a Jew named Apollos, an eloquent speaker who knew the
        Scriptures well, had arrived in Ephesus from Alexandria in Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He had been taught the way of the Lord, and he taught others about
        Jesus with an enthusiastic spirit[COMMENT[0]] and with accuracy. However,
        he knew only about John\u2019s baptism. "
      comments:
      - number: '18:25 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: with enthusiasm in the Spirit.
    - title: 
      content: 'When Priscilla and Aquila heard him preaching boldly in the synagogue,
        they took him aside and explained the way of God even more accurately.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Apollos had been thinking about going to Achaia, and the brothers
        and sisters in Ephesus encouraged him to go. They wrote to the believers
        in Achaia, asking them to welcome him. When he arrived there, he proved to
        be of great benefit to those who, by God\u2019s grace, had believed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: He refuted the Jews with powerful arguments in public debate. Using
        the Scriptures, he explained to them that Jesus was the Messiah.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Paul\u2019s Third Missionary Journey"
      content: 'While Apollos was in Corinth, Paul traveled through the interior
        regions until he reached Ephesus, on the coast, where he found several believers.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '19:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'disciples; '
        - ft: also in 19:9, 30.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDid you receive the Holy Spirit when you believed?\u201D he
        asked them.\n\t\u201CNo,\u201D they replied, \u201Cwe haven\u2019t even heard
        that there is a Holy Spirit.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen what baptism did you experience?\u201D he asked.\n\tAnd
        they replied, \u201CThe baptism of John.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Paul said, \u201CJohn\u2019s baptism called for repentance from sin.
        But John himself told the people to believe in the one who would come later,
        meaning Jesus.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as they heard this, they were baptized in the name of the
        Lord Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then when Paul laid his hands on them, the Holy Spirit came on them,
        and they spoke in other tongues[COMMENT[0]] and prophesied. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: in other languages.
    - title: 
      content: 'There were about twelve men in all.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Ministers in Ephesus
      content: 'Then Paul went to the synagogue and preached boldly for the next
        three months, arguing persuasively about the Kingdom of God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But some became stubborn, rejecting his message and publicly speaking
        against the Way. So Paul left the synagogue and took the believers with him.
        Then he held daily discussions at the lecture hall of Tyrannus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This went on for the next two years, so that people throughout the
        province of Asia\u2014both Jews and Greeks\u2014heard the word of the Lord.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'God gave Paul the power to perform unusual miracles. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When handkerchiefs or aprons that had merely touched his skin were
        placed on sick people, they were healed of their diseases, and evil spirits
        were expelled.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A group of Jews was traveling from town to town casting out evil
        spirits. They tried to use the name of the Lord Jesus in their incantation,
        saying, \u201CI command you in the name of Jesus, whom Paul preaches, to
        come out!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Seven sons of Sceva, a leading priest, were doing this. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But one time when they tried it, the evil spirit replied, \u201CI
        know Jesus, and I know Paul, but who are you?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the man with the evil spirit leaped on them, overpowered them,
        and attacked them with such violence that they fled from the house, naked
        and battered.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The story of what happened spread quickly all through Ephesus, to
        Jews and Greeks alike. A solemn fear descended on the city, and the name
        of the Lord Jesus was greatly honored. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Many who became believers confessed their sinful practices. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A number of them who had been practicing sorcery brought their incantation
        books and burned them at a public bonfire. The value of the books was several
        million dollars.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '19:19 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: '50,000 pieces of silver, '
        - ft: "each of which was the equivalent of a day\u2019s wage."
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'So the message about the Lord spread widely and had a powerful effect.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Afterward Paul felt compelled by the Spirit[COMMENT[0]] to go over
        to Macedonia and Achaia before going to Jerusalem. \u201CAnd after that,\u201D
        he said, \u201CI must go on to Rome!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '19:21 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: decided in his spirit.
    - title: 
      content: 'He sent his two assistants, Timothy and Erastus, ahead to Macedonia
        while he stayed awhile longer in the province of Asia.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Riot in Ephesus
      content: 'About that time, serious trouble developed in Ephesus concerning
        the Way. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It began with Demetrius, a silversmith who had a large business manufacturing
        silver shrines of the Greek goddess Artemis.[COMMENT[0]] He kept many craftsmen
        busy. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:24 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Artemis '
        - ft: is otherwise known as Diana.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "He called them together, along with others employed in similar trades,
        and addressed them as follows:\n\t\u201CGentlemen, you know that our wealth
        comes from this business. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But as you have seen and heard, this man Paul has persuaded many
        people that handmade gods aren\u2019t really gods at all. And he\u2019s done
        this not only here in Ephesus but throughout the entire province! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Of course, I\u2019m not just talking about the loss of public respect
        for our business. I\u2019m also concerned that the temple of the great goddess
        Artemis will lose its influence and that Artemis\u2014this magnificent goddess
        worshiped throughout the province of Asia and all around the world\u2014will
        be robbed of her great prestige!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At this their anger boiled, and they began shouting, \u201CGreat
        is Artemis of the Ephesians!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Soon the whole city was filled with confusion. Everyone rushed to
        the amphitheater, dragging along Gaius and Aristarchus, who were Paul\u2019s
        traveling companions from Macedonia. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Paul wanted to go in, too, but the believers wouldn\u2019t let him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some of the officials of the province, friends of Paul, also sent
        a message to him, begging him not to risk his life by entering the amphitheater.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Inside, the people were all shouting, some one thing and some another.
        Everything was in confusion. In fact, most of them didn\u2019t even know
        why they were there. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Jews in the crowd pushed Alexander forward and told him to explain
        the situation. He motioned for silence and tried to speak. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when the crowd realized he was a Jew, they started shouting again
        and kept it up for about two hours: \u201CGreat is Artemis of the Ephesians!
        Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At last the mayor was able to quiet them down enough to speak. \u201CCitizens
        of Ephesus,\u201D he said. \u201CEveryone knows that Ephesus is the official
        guardian of the temple of the great Artemis, whose image fell down to us
        from heaven. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Since this is an undeniable fact, you should stay calm and not do
        anything rash. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You have brought these men here, but they have stolen nothing from
        the temple and have not spoken against our goddess.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf Demetrius and the craftsmen have a case against them, the
        courts are in session and the officials can hear the case at once. Let them
        make formal charges. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And if there are complaints about other matters, they can be settled
        in a legal assembly. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I am afraid we are in danger of being charged with rioting by the
        Roman government, since there is no cause for all this commotion. And if
        Rome demands an explanation, we won\u2019t know what to say.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '[COMMENT[0]]Then he dismissed them, and they dispersed.'
      comments:
      - number: '19:41 '
        contents:
        - ft: Some translations include verse 41 as part of verse 40.
          body: 
  - verses:
    - title: Paul Goes to Macedonia and Greece
      content: 'When the uproar was over, Paul sent for the believers[COMMENT[0]]
        and encouraged them. Then he said good-bye and left for Macedonia. '
      comments:
      - number: '20:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: disciples.
    - title: 
      content: 'While there, he encouraged the believers in all the towns he passed
        through. Then he traveled down to Greece, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'where he stayed for three months. He was preparing to sail back to
        Syria when he discovered a plot by some Jews against his life, so he decided
        to return through Macedonia.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Several men were traveling with him. They were Sopater son of Pyrrhus
        from Berea; Aristarchus and Secundus from Thessalonica; Gaius from Derbe;
        Timothy; and Tychicus and Trophimus from the province of Asia. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They went on ahead and waited for us at Troas. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the Passover[COMMENT[0]] ended, we boarded a ship at Philippi
        in Macedonia and five days later joined them in Troas, where we stayed a
        week.  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the days of unleavened bread.
    - title: "Paul\u2019s Final Visit to Troas"
      content: "On the first day of the week, we gathered with the local believers
        to share in the Lord\u2019s Supper.[COMMENT[0]] Paul was preaching to them,
        and since he was leaving the next day, he kept talking until midnight. "
      comments:
      - number: '20:7 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: to break bread.
    - title: 
      content: 'The upstairs room where we met was lighted with many flickering lamps. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As Paul spoke on and on, a young man named Eutychus, sitting on the
        windowsill, became very drowsy. Finally, he fell sound asleep and dropped
        three stories to his death below. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Paul went down, bent over him, and took him into his arms. \u201CDon\u2019t
        worry,\u201D he said, \u201Che\u2019s alive!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then they all went back upstairs, shared in the Lord\u2019s Supper,[COMMENT[0]]
        and ate together. Paul continued talking to them until dawn, and then he
        left. "
      comments:
      - number: '20:11 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: broke the bread.
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, the young man was taken home alive and well, and everyone
        was greatly relieved.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Meets the Ephesian Elders
      content: 'Paul went by land to Assos, where he had arranged for us to join
        him, while we traveled by ship. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He joined us there, and we sailed together to Mitylene. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next day we sailed past the island of Kios. The following day
        we crossed to the island of Samos, and[COMMENT[0]] a day later we arrived
        at Miletus.  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: and having stayed at Trogyllium.
    - title: 
      content: "Paul had decided to sail on past Ephesus, for he didn\u2019t want
        to spend any more time in the province of Asia. He was hurrying to get to
        Jerusalem, if possible, in time for the Festival of Pentecost. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when we landed at Miletus, he sent a message to the elders of
        the church at Ephesus, asking them to come and meet him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they arrived he declared, \u201CYou know that from the day I
        set foot in the province of Asia until now "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have done the Lord\u2019s work humbly and with many tears. I have
        endured the trials that came to me from the plots of the Jews. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I never shrank back from telling you what you needed to hear, either
        publicly or in your homes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have had one message for Jews and Greeks alike\u2014the necessity
        of repenting from sin and turning to God, and of having faith in our Lord
        Jesus.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd now I am bound by the Spirit[COMMENT[0]] to go to Jerusalem.
        I don\u2019t know what awaits me, "
      comments:
      - number: '20:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'by my spirit, '
        - ft: 'or '
          body: 'by an inner compulsion; '
        - ft: 'Greek reads '
          body: by the spirit.
    - title: 
      content: 'except that the Holy Spirit tells me in city after city that jail
        and suffering lie ahead. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But my life is worth nothing to me unless I use it for finishing
        the work assigned me by the Lord Jesus\u2014the work of telling others the
        Good News about the wonderful grace of God.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd now I know that none of you to whom I have preached the
        Kingdom will ever see me again. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I declare today that I have been faithful. If anyone suffers eternal
        death, it\u2019s not my fault,[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:26 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: I am innocent of the blood of all.
    - title: 
      content: "for I didn\u2019t shrink from declaring all that God wants you to
        know.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo guard yourselves and God\u2019s people. Feed and shepherd
        God\u2019s flock\u2014his church, purchased with his own blood[COMMENT[0]]\u2014over
        which the Holy Spirit has appointed you as leaders.[COMMENT[1]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:28a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: with the blood of his own [Son].
      - number: '20:28b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'overseers, '
        - ft: 'or '
          body: bishops.
    - title: 
      content: 'I know that false teachers, like vicious wolves, will come in among
        you after I leave, not sparing the flock. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even some men from your own group will rise up and distort the truth
        in order to draw a following. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Watch out! Remember the three years I was with you\u2014my constant
        watch and care over you night and day, and my many tears for you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd now I entrust you to God and the message of his grace that
        is able to build you up and give you an inheritance with all those he has
        set apart for himself.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI have never coveted anyone\u2019s silver or gold or fine clothes. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You know that these hands of mine have worked to supply my own needs
        and even the needs of those who were with me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I have been a constant example of how you can help those in need
        by working hard. You should remember the words of the Lord Jesus: \n\t\u2018It
        is more blessed to give than to receive.\u2019\n\t\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When he had finished speaking, he knelt and prayed with them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They all cried as they embraced and kissed him good-bye. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: They were sad most of all because he had said that they would never
        see him again. Then they escorted him down to the ship.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Paul\u2019s Journey to Jerusalem"
      content: 'After saying farewell to the Ephesian elders, we sailed straight
        to the island of Cos. The next day we reached Rhodes and then went to Patara. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There we boarded a ship sailing for Phoenicia. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We sighted the island of Cyprus, passed it on our left, and landed
        at the harbor of Tyre, in Syria, where the ship was to unload its cargo.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We went ashore, found the local believers,[COMMENT[0]] and stayed
        with them a week. These believers prophesied through the Holy Spirit that
        Paul should not go on to Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: '21:4 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'disciples; '
        - ft: also in 21:16.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'When we returned to the ship at the end of the week, the entire congregation,
        including women[COMMENT[0]] and children, left the city and came down to
        the shore with us. There we knelt, prayed, '
      comments:
      - number: '21:5 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: wives.
    - title: 
      content: 'and said our farewells. Then we went aboard, and they returned home.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next stop after leaving Tyre was Ptolemais, where we greeted
        the brothers and sisters[COMMENT[0]] and stayed for one day. '
      comments:
      - number: '21:7 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'brothers; '
        - ft: also in 21:17.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'The next day we went on to Caesarea and stayed at the home of Philip
        the Evangelist, one of the seven men who had been chosen to distribute food. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He had four unmarried daughters who had the gift of prophecy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Several days later a man named Agabus, who also had the gift of prophecy,
        arrived from Judea. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He came over, took Paul\u2019s belt, and bound his own feet and hands
        with it. Then he said, \u201CThe Holy Spirit declares, \u2018So shall the
        owner of this belt be bound by the Jewish leaders in Jerusalem and turned
        over to the Gentiles.\u2019\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When we heard this, we and the local believers all begged Paul not
        to go on to Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But he said, \u201CWhy all this weeping? You are breaking my heart!
        I am ready not only to be jailed at Jerusalem but even to die for the sake
        of the Lord Jesus.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When it was clear that we couldn\u2019t persuade him, we gave up
        and said, \u201CThe Lord\u2019s will be done.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Arrives at Jerusalem
      content: 'After this we packed our things and left for Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some believers from Caesarea accompanied us, and they took us to
        the home of Mnason, a man originally from Cyprus and one of the early believers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When we arrived, the brothers and sisters in Jerusalem welcomed us
        warmly.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next day Paul went with us to meet with James, and all the elders
        of the Jerusalem church were present. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After greeting them, Paul gave a detailed account of the things God
        had accomplished among the Gentiles through his ministry.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After hearing this, they praised God. And then they said, \u201CYou
        know, dear brother, how many thousands of Jews have also believed, and they
        all follow the law of Moses very seriously. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the Jewish believers here in Jerusalem have been told that you
        are teaching all the Jews who live among the Gentiles to turn their backs
        on the laws of Moses. They\u2019ve heard that you teach them not to circumcise
        their children or follow other Jewish customs. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'What should we do? They will certainly hear that you have come.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHere\u2019s what we want you to do. We have four men here who
        have completed their vow. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Go with them to the Temple and join them in the purification ceremony,
        paying for them to have their heads ritually shaved. Then everyone will know
        that the rumors are all false and that you yourself observe the Jewish laws.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAs for the Gentile believers, they should do what we already
        told them in a letter: They should abstain from eating food offered to idols,
        from consuming blood or the meat of strangled animals, and from sexual immorality.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Is Arrested
      content: 'So Paul went to the Temple the next day with the other men. They
        had already started the purification ritual, so he publicly announced the
        date when their vows would end and sacrifices would be offered for each of
        them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The seven days were almost ended when some Jews from the province
        of Asia saw Paul in the Temple and roused a mob against him. They grabbed
        him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "yelling, \u201CMen of Israel, help us! This is the man who preaches
        against our people everywhere and tells everybody to disobey the Jewish laws.
        He speaks against the Temple\u2014and even defiles this holy place by bringing
        in Gentiles.[COMMENT[0]]\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '21:28 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Greeks.
    - title: 
      content: '(For earlier that day they had seen him in the city with Trophimus,
        a Gentile from Ephesus,[COMMENT[0]] and they assumed Paul had taken him into
        the Temple.)  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:29 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Trophimus, the Ephesian.
    - title: 
      content: 'The whole city was rocked by these accusations, and a great riot
        followed. Paul was grabbed and dragged out of the Temple, and immediately
        the gates were closed behind him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As they were trying to kill him, word reached the commander of the
        Roman regiment that all Jerusalem was in an uproar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He immediately called out his soldiers and officers[COMMENT[0]] and
        ran down among the crowd. When the mob saw the commander and the troops coming,
        they stopped beating Paul.  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:32 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: centurions.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the commander arrested him and ordered him bound with two chains.
        He asked the crowd who he was and what he had done. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Some shouted one thing and some another. Since he couldn\u2019t find
        out the truth in all the uproar and confusion, he ordered that Paul be taken
        to the fortress. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As Paul reached the stairs, the mob grew so violent the soldiers
        had to lift him to their shoulders to protect him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the crowd followed behind, shouting, \u201CKill him, kill him!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Speaks to the Crowd
      content: "As Paul was about to be taken inside, he said to the commander, \u201CMay
        I have a word with you?\u201D\n\t\u201CDo you know Greek?\u201D the commander
        asked, surprised. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAren\u2019t you the Egyptian who led a rebellion some time
        ago and took 4,000 members of the Assassins out into the desert?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo,\u201D Paul replied, \u201CI am a Jew and a citizen of Tarsus
        in Cilicia, which is an important city. Please, let me talk to these people.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: The commander agreed, so Paul stood on the stairs and motioned to
        the people to be quiet. Soon a deep silence enveloped the crowd, and he addressed
        them in their own language, Aramaic.[COMMENT[0]]
      comments:
      - number: '21:40 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Hebrew.
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBrothers and esteemed fathers,\u201D Paul said, \u201Clisten
        to me as I offer my defense.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they heard him speaking in their own language,[COMMENT[0]] the
        silence was even greater.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'in Aramaic, '
        - ft: 'or '
          body: in Hebrew.
    - title: 
      content: "Then Paul said, \u201CI am a Jew, born in Tarsus, a city in Cilicia,
        and I was brought up and educated here in Jerusalem under Gamaliel. As his
        student, I was carefully trained in our Jewish laws and customs. I became
        very zealous to honor God in everything I did, just like all of you today. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I persecuted the followers of the Way, hounding some to death,
        arresting both men and women and throwing them in prison. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The high priest and the whole council of elders can testify that
        this is so. For I received letters from them to our Jewish brothers in Damascus,
        authorizing me to bring the followers of the Way from there to Jerusalem,
        in chains, to be punished.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAs I was on the road, approaching Damascus about noon, a very
        bright light from heaven suddenly shone down around me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I fell to the ground and heard a voice saying to me, \n\t\u2018Saul,
        Saul, why are you persecuting me?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201C\u2018Who are you, lord?\u2019 I asked.\n\t\u201CAnd the voice
        replied, \n\t\u2018I am Jesus the Nazarene,[COMMENT[0]]  \n\tthe one you
        are persecuting.\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:8 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Jesus of Nazareth.
    - title: 
      content: "The people with me saw the light but didn\u2019t understand the voice
        speaking to me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI asked, \u2018What should I do, Lord?\u2019\n\t\u201CAnd the
        Lord told me, \n\t\u2018Get up and go into Damascus, and there you will be
        told everything you are to do.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI was blinded by the intense light and had to be led by the
        hand to Damascus by my companions. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A man named Ananias lived there. He was a godly man, deeply devoted
        to the law, and well regarded by all the Jews of Damascus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He came and stood beside me and said, \u2018Brother Saul, regain
        your sight.\u2019 And that very moment I could see him!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen he told me, \u2018The God of our ancestors has chosen
        you to know his will and to see the Righteous One and hear him speak. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For you are to be his witness, telling everyone what you have seen
        and heard. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What are you waiting for? Get up and be baptized. Have your sins
        washed away by calling on the name of the Lord.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAfter I returned to Jerusalem, I was praying in the Temple
        and fell into a trance. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I saw a vision of Jesus[COMMENT[0]] saying to me, \n\t\u2018Hurry!
        Leave Jerusalem, for the people here won\u2019t accept your testimony about
        me.\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:18 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: him.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201C\u2018But Lord,\u2019 I argued, \u2018they certainly know that
        in every synagogue I imprisoned and beat those who believed in you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I was in complete agreement when your witness Stephen was killed.
        I stood by and kept the coats they took off when they stoned him.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut the Lord said to me, \n\t\u2018Go, for I will send you
        far away to the Gentiles!\u2019\n\t\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The crowd listened until Paul said that word. Then they all began
        to shout, \u201CAway with such a fellow! He isn\u2019t fit to live!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They yelled, threw off their coats, and tossed handfuls of dust into
        the air.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Reveals His Roman Citizenship
      content: 'The commander brought Paul inside and ordered him lashed with whips
        to make him confess his crime. He wanted to find out why the crowd had become
        so furious. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they tied Paul down to lash him, Paul said to the officer[COMMENT[0]]
        standing there, \u201CIs it legal for you to whip a Roman citizen who hasn\u2019t
        even been tried?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:25 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'the centurion; '
        - ft: also in 22:26.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "When the officer heard this, he went to the commander and asked,
        \u201CWhat are you doing? This man is a Roman citizen!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the commander went over and asked Paul, \u201CTell me, are you
        a Roman citizen?\u201D\n\t\u201CYes, I certainly am,\u201D Paul replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am, too,\u201D the commander muttered, \u201Cand it cost
        me plenty!\u201D\n\tPaul answered, \u201CBut I am a citizen by birth!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The soldiers who were about to interrogate Paul quickly withdrew
        when they heard he was a Roman citizen, and the commander was frightened
        because he had ordered him bound and whipped.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul before the High Council
      content: The next day the commander ordered the leading priests into session
        with the Jewish high council.[COMMENT[0]] He wanted to find out what the
        trouble was all about, so he released Paul to have him stand before them.
      comments:
      - number: '22:30 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Sanhedrin.
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "Gazing intently at the high council,[COMMENT[0]] Paul began: \u201CBrothers,
        I have always lived before God with a clear conscience!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'Sanhedrin; '
        - ft: also in 23:6, 15, 20, 28.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Instantly Ananias the high priest commanded those close to Paul to
        slap him on the mouth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Paul said to him, \u201CGod will slap you, you corrupt hypocrite![COMMENT[0]]
        What kind of judge are you to break the law yourself by ordering me struck
        like that?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:3 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: you whitewashed wall.
    - title: 
      content: "Those standing near Paul said to him, \u201CDo you dare to insult
        God\u2019s high priest?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI\u2019m sorry, brothers. I didn\u2019t realize he was the
        high priest,\u201D Paul replied, \u201Cfor the Scriptures say, \u2018You
        must not speak evil of any of your rulers.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:5 '
        contents:
        - ft: Exod 22:28.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Paul realized that some members of the high council were Sadducees
        and some were Pharisees, so he shouted, \u201CBrothers, I am a Pharisee,
        as were my ancestors! And I am on trial because my hope is in the resurrection
        of the dead!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This divided the council\u2014the Pharisees against the Sadducees\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'for the Sadducees say there is no resurrection or angels or spirits,
        but the Pharisees believe in all of these. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So there was a great uproar. Some of the teachers of religious law
        who were Pharisees jumped up and began to argue forcefully. \u201CWe see
        nothing wrong with him,\u201D they shouted. \u201CPerhaps a spirit or an
        angel spoke to him.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As the conflict grew more violent, the commander was afraid they
        would tear Paul apart. So he ordered his soldiers to go and rescue him by
        force and take him back to the fortress.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "That night the Lord appeared to Paul and said, \n\t\u201CBe encouraged,
        Paul. Just as you have been a witness to me here in Jerusalem, you must preach
        the Good News in Rome as well.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Plan to Kill Paul
      content: 'The next morning a group of Jews[COMMENT[0]] got together and bound
        themselves with an oath not to eat or drink until they had killed Paul. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: the Jews.
    - title: 
      content: 'There were more than forty of them in the conspiracy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They went to the leading priests and elders and told them, \u201CWe
        have bound ourselves with an oath to eat nothing until we have killed Paul. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So you and the high council should ask the commander to bring Paul
        back to the council again. Pretend you want to examine his case more fully.
        We will kill him on the way.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Paul\u2019s nephew\u2014his sister\u2019s son\u2014heard of their
        plan and went to the fortress and told Paul. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Paul called for one of the Roman officers[COMMENT[0]] and said, \u201CTake
        this young man to the commander. He has something important to tell him.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:17 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'centurions; '
        - ft: also in 23:23.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "So the officer did, explaining, \u201CPaul, the prisoner, called
        me over and asked me to bring this young man to you because he has something
        to tell you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The commander took his hand, led him aside, and asked, \u201CWhat
        is it you want to tell me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Paul\u2019s nephew told him, \u201CSome Jews are going to ask you
        to bring Paul before the high council tomorrow, pretending they want to get
        some more information. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But don\u2019t do it! There are more than forty men hiding along
        the way ready to ambush him. They have vowed not to eat or drink anything
        until they have killed him. They are ready now, just waiting for your consent.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t let anyone know you told me this,\u201D the commander
        warned the young man.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Is Sent to Caesarea
      content: "Then the commander called two of his officers and ordered, \u201CGet
        200 soldiers ready to leave for Caesarea at nine o\u2019clock tonight. Also
        take 200 spearmen and 70 mounted troops. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Provide horses for Paul to ride, and get him safely to Governor Felix.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he wrote this letter to the governor:  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFrom Claudius Lysias, to his Excellency, Governor Felix: Greetings!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis man was seized by some Jews, and they were about to kill
        him when I arrived with the troops. When I learned that he was a Roman citizen,
        I removed him to safety. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then I took him to their high council to try to learn the basis of
        the accusations against him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I soon discovered the charge was something regarding their religious
        law\u2014certainly nothing worthy of imprisonment or death. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when I was informed of a plot to kill him, I immediately sent
        him on to you. I have told his accusers to bring their charges before you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So that night, as ordered, the soldiers took Paul as far as Antipatris. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They returned to the fortress the next morning, while the mounted
        troops took him on to Caesarea. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they arrived in Caesarea, they presented Paul and the letter
        to Governor Felix. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He read it and then asked Paul what province he was from. \u201CCilicia,\u201D
        Paul answered.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI will hear your case myself when your accusers arrive,\u201D
        the governor told him. Then the governor ordered him kept in the prison at
        Herod\u2019s headquarters.[COMMENT[0]]"
      comments:
      - number: '23:35 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: "Herod\u2019s Praetorium."
  - verses:
    - title: Paul Appears before Felix
      content: 'Five days later Ananias, the high priest, arrived with some of the
        Jewish elders and the lawyer[COMMENT[0]] Tertullus, to present their case
        against Paul to the governor. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: some elders and an orator.
    - title: 
      content: "When Paul was called in, Tertullus presented the charges against
        Paul in the following address to the governor:\n\t\u201CYou have provided
        a long period of peace for us Jews and with foresight have enacted reforms
        for us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For all of this, Your Excellency, we are very grateful to you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I don\u2019t want to bore you, so please give me your attention
        for only a moment. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We have found this man to be a troublemaker who is constantly stirring
        up riots among the Jews all over the world. He is a ringleader of the cult
        known as the Nazarenes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Furthermore, he was trying to desecrate the Temple when we arrested
        him.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '24:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts add an expanded conclusion to verse 6, all of verse
            7, and an additional phrase in verse 8: '
          body: commanding his accusers to come before you.
    - title: 
      content: "You can find out the truth of our accusations by examining him yourself.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the other Jews chimed in, declaring that everything Tertullus
        said was true.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The governor then motioned for Paul to speak. Paul said, \u201CI
        know, sir, that you have been a judge of Jewish affairs for many years, so
        I gladly present my defense before you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You can quickly discover that I arrived in Jerusalem no more than
        twelve days ago to worship at the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'My accusers never found me arguing with anyone in the Temple, nor
        stirring up a riot in any synagogue or on the streets of the city. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These men cannot prove the things they accuse me of doing.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut I admit that I follow the Way, which they call a cult.
        I worship the God of our ancestors, and I firmly believe the Jewish law and
        everything written in the prophets. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I have the same hope in God that these men have, that he will raise
        both the righteous and the unrighteous. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Because of this, I always try to maintain a clear conscience before
        God and all people.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAfter several years away, I returned to Jerusalem with money
        to aid my people and to offer sacrifices to God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'My accusers saw me in the Temple as I was completing a purification
        ceremony. There was no crowd around me and no rioting. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But some Jews from the province of Asia were there\u2014and they
        ought to be here to bring charges if they have anything against me! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ask these men here what crime the Jewish high council[COMMENT[0]]
        found me guilty of, '
      comments:
      - number: '24:20 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Sanhedrin.
    - title: 
      content: "except for the one time I shouted out, \u2018I am on trial before
        you today because I believe in the resurrection of the dead!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At that point Felix, who was quite familiar with the Way, adjourned
        the hearing and said, \u201CWait until Lysias, the garrison commander, arrives.
        Then I will decide the case.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He ordered an officer[COMMENT[0]] to keep Paul in custody but to
        give him some freedom and allow his friends to visit him and take care of
        his needs.  '
      comments:
      - number: '24:23 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: a centurion.
    - title: 
      content: 'A few days later Felix came back with his wife, Drusilla, who was
        Jewish. Sending for Paul, they listened as he told them about faith in Christ
        Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As he reasoned with them about righteousness and self-control and
        the coming day of judgment, Felix became frightened. \u201CGo away for now,\u201D
        he replied. \u201CWhen it is more convenient, I\u2019ll call for you again.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also hoped that Paul would bribe him, so he sent for him quite
        often and talked with him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: After two years went by in this way, Felix was succeeded by Porcius
        Festus. And because Felix wanted to gain favor with the Jewish people, he
        left Paul in prison.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Paul Appears before Festus
      content: 'Three days after Festus arrived in Caesarea to take over his new
        responsibilities, he left for Jerusalem, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'where the leading priests and other Jewish leaders met with him and
        made their accusations against Paul. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They asked Festus as a favor to transfer Paul to Jerusalem (planning
        to ambush and kill him on the way). '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Festus replied that Paul was at Caesarea and he himself would
        be returning there soon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So he said, \u201CThose of you in authority can return with me. If
        Paul has done anything wrong, you can make your accusations.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'About eight or ten days later Festus returned to Caesarea, and on
        the following day he took his seat in court and ordered that Paul be brought
        in. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Paul arrived, the Jewish leaders from Jerusalem gathered around
        and made many serious accusations they couldn\u2019t prove.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Paul denied the charges. \u201CI am not guilty of any crime against
        the Jewish laws or the Temple or the Roman government,\u201D he said.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Festus, wanting to please the Jews, asked him, \u201CAre you
        willing to go to Jerusalem and stand trial before me there?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Paul replied, \u201CNo! This is the official Roman court, so
        I ought to be tried right here. You know very well I am not guilty of harming
        the Jews. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If I have done something worthy of death, I don\u2019t refuse to
        die. But if I am innocent, no one has a right to turn me over to these men
        to kill me. I appeal to Caesar!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Festus conferred with his advisers and then replied, \u201CVery well!
        You have appealed to Caesar, and to Caesar you will go!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A few days later King Agrippa arrived with his sister, Bernice,[COMMENT[0]]
        to pay their respects to Festus. '
      comments:
      - number: '25:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: Agrippa the king and Bernice arrived.
    - title: 
      content: "During their stay of several days, Festus discussed Paul\u2019s case
        with the king. \u201CThere is a prisoner here,\u201D he told him, \u201Cwhose
        case was left for me by Felix. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I was in Jerusalem, the leading priests and Jewish elders pressed
        charges against him and asked me to condemn him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I pointed out to them that Roman law does not convict people without
        a trial. They must be given an opportunity to confront their accusers and
        defend themselves.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen his accusers came here for the trial, I didn\u2019t delay.
        I called the case the very next day and ordered Paul brought in. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the accusations made against him weren\u2019t any of the crimes
        I expected. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Instead, it was something about their religion and a dead man named
        Jesus, who Paul insists is alive. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I was at a loss to know how to investigate these things, so I asked
        him whether he would be willing to stand trial on these charges in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Paul appealed to have his case decided by the emperor. So I ordered
        that he be held in custody until I could arrange to send him to Caesar.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI\u2019d like to hear the man myself,\u201D Agrippa said.\n\tAnd
        Festus replied, \u201CYou will\u2014tomorrow!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Speaks to Agrippa
      content: 'So the next day Agrippa and Bernice arrived at the auditorium with
        great pomp, accompanied by military officers and prominent men of the city.
        Festus ordered that Paul be brought in. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Festus said, \u201CKing Agrippa and all who are here, this is
        the man whose death is demanded by all the Jews, both here and in Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But in my opinion he has done nothing deserving death. However, since
        he appealed his case to the emperor, I have decided to send him to Rome.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut what shall I write the emperor? For there is no clear charge
        against him. So I have brought him before all of you, and especially you,
        King Agrippa, so that after we examine him, I might have something to write. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For it makes no sense to send a prisoner to the emperor without specifying
        the charges against him!\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "Then Agrippa said to Paul, \u201CYou may speak in your defense.\u201D\n\tSo
        Paul, gesturing with his hand, started his defense: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am fortunate, King Agrippa, that you are the one hearing
        my defense today against all these accusations made by the Jewish leaders, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'for I know you are an expert on all Jewish customs and controversies.
        Now please listen to me patiently!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAs the Jewish leaders are well aware, I was given a thorough
        Jewish training from my earliest childhood among my own people and in Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If they would admit it, they know that I have been a member of the
        Pharisees, the strictest sect of our religion. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now I am on trial because of my hope in the fulfillment of God\u2019s
        promise made to our ancestors. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In fact, that is why the twelve tribes of Israel zealously worship
        God night and day, and they share the same hope I have. Yet, Your Majesty,
        they accuse me for having this hope! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Why does it seem incredible to any of you that God can raise the
        dead?  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI used to believe that I ought to do everything I could to
        oppose the very name of Jesus the Nazarene.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:9 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Jesus of Nazareth.
    - title: 
      content: 'Indeed, I did just that in Jerusalem. Authorized by the leading priests,
        I caused many believers[COMMENT[0]] there to be sent to prison. And I cast
        my vote against them when they were condemned to death. '
      comments:
      - number: '26:10 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: "many of God\u2019s holy people."
    - title: 
      content: 'Many times I had them punished in the synagogues to get them to curse
        Jesus.[COMMENT[0]] I was so violently opposed to them that I even chased
        them down in foreign cities.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:11 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: to blaspheme.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COne day I was on such a mission to Damascus, armed with the
        authority and commission of the leading priests. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'About noon, Your Majesty, as I was on the road, a light from heaven
        brighter than the sun shone down on me and my companions. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We all fell down, and I heard a voice saying to me in Aramaic,[COMMENT[0]] 
        \n\t\u2018Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? It is useless for you to
        fight against my will.[COMMENT[1]]\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:14a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Hebrew.
      - number: '26:14b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: It is hard for you to kick against the oxgoads.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201C\u2018Who are you, lord?\u2019 I asked.\n\t\u201CAnd the Lord
        replied, \n\t\u2018I am Jesus, the one you are persecuting.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now get to your feet! For I have appeared to you to appoint you as
        my servant and witness. Tell people that you have seen me, and tell them
        what I will show you in the future.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will rescue you from both your own people and the Gentiles.
        Yes, I am sending you to the Gentiles  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "to open their eyes, so they may turn from darkness to light and from
        the power of Satan to God. Then they will receive forgiveness for their sins
        and be given a place among God\u2019s people, who are set apart by faith
        in me.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd so, King Agrippa, I obeyed that vision from heaven. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I preached first to those in Damascus, then in Jerusalem and throughout
        all Judea, and also to the Gentiles, that all must repent of their sins and
        turn to God\u2014and prove they have changed by the good things they do. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some Jews arrested me in the Temple for preaching this, and they
        tried to kill me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But God has protected me right up to this present time so I can testify
        to everyone, from the least to the greatest. I teach nothing except what
        the prophets and Moses said would happen\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "that the Messiah would suffer and be the first to rise from the dead,
        and in this way announce God\u2019s light to Jews and Gentiles alike.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Suddenly, Festus shouted, \u201CPaul, you are insane. Too much study
        has made you crazy!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Paul replied, \u201CI am not insane, Most Excellent Festus. What
        I am saying is the sober truth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And King Agrippa knows about these things. I speak boldly, for I
        am sure these events are all familiar to him, for they were not done in a
        corner! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know you do\u2014\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Agrippa interrupted him. \u201CDo you think you can persuade me to
        become a Christian so quickly?\u201D[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:28 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: "\u201CA little more, and your arguments would make me a Christian.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "Paul replied, \u201CWhether quickly or not, I pray to God that both
        you and everyone here in this audience might become the same as I am, except
        for these chains.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the king, the governor, Bernice, and all the others stood and
        left. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As they went out, they talked it over and agreed, \u201CThis man
        hasn\u2019t done anything to deserve death or imprisonment.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Agrippa said to Festus, \u201CHe could have been set free if
        he hadn\u2019t appealed to Caesar.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Paul Sails for Rome
      content: 'When the time came, we set sail for Italy. Paul and several other
        prisoners were placed in the custody of a Roman officer[COMMENT[0]] named
        Julius, a captain of the Imperial Regiment. '
      comments:
      - number: '27:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'centurion; '
        - ft: similarly in 27:6, 11, 31, 43.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Aristarchus, a Macedonian from Thessalonica, was also with us. We
        left on a ship whose home port was Adramyttium on the northwest coast of
        the province of Asia;[COMMENT[0]] it was scheduled to make several stops
        at ports along the coast of the province.  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Asia '
        - ft: was a Roman province in what is now western Turkey.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'The next day when we docked at Sidon, Julius was very kind to Paul
        and let him go ashore to visit with friends so they could provide for his
        needs. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Putting out to sea from there, we encountered strong headwinds that
        made it difficult to keep the ship on course, so we sailed north of Cyprus
        between the island and the mainland. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Keeping to the open sea, we passed along the coast of Cilicia and
        Pamphylia, landing at Myra, in the province of Lycia. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There the commanding officer found an Egyptian ship from Alexandria
        that was bound for Italy, and he put us on board.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We had several days of slow sailing, and after great difficulty we
        finally neared Cnidus. But the wind was against us, so we sailed across to
        Crete and along the sheltered coast of the island, past the cape of Salmone. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We struggled along the coast with great difficulty and finally arrived
        at Fair Havens, near the town of Lasea. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We had lost a lot of time. The weather was becoming dangerous for
        sea travel because it was so late in the fall,[COMMENT[0]] and Paul spoke
        to the ship\u2019s officers about it.  "
      comments:
      - number: '27:9 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: 'because the fast was now already gone by. '
        - ft: This fast was associated with the Day of Atonement (
          body: Yom Kippur
        - ft: ), which occurred in late September or early October.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMen,\u201D he said, \u201CI believe there is trouble ahead
        if we go on\u2014shipwreck, loss of cargo, and danger to our lives as well.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the officer in charge of the prisoners listened more to the ship\u2019s
        captain and the owner than to Paul. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And since Fair Havens was an exposed harbor\u2014a poor place to
        spend the winter\u2014most of the crew wanted to go on to Phoenix, farther
        up the coast of Crete, and spend the winter there. Phoenix was a good harbor
        with only a southwest and northwest exposure.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Storm at Sea
      content: 'When a light wind began blowing from the south, the sailors thought
        they could make it. So they pulled up anchor and sailed close to the shore
        of Crete. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the weather changed abruptly, and a wind of typhoon strength
        (called a \u201Cnortheaster\u201D) burst across the island and blew us out
        to sea. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The sailors couldn\u2019t turn the ship into the wind, so they gave
        up and let it run before the gale.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We sailed along the sheltered side of a small island named Cauda,[COMMENT[0]]
        where with great difficulty we hoisted aboard the lifeboat being towed behind
        us. '
      comments:
      - number: '27:16 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts read '
          body: Clauda.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the sailors bound ropes around the hull of the ship to strengthen
        it. They were afraid of being driven across to the sandbars of Syrtis off
        the African coast, so they lowered the sea anchor to slow the ship and were
        driven before the wind.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next day, as gale-force winds continued to batter the ship, the
        crew began throwing the cargo overboard. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The following day they even took some of the ship\u2019s gear and
        threw it overboard. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The terrible storm raged for many days, blotting out the sun and
        the stars, until at last all hope was gone.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No one had eaten for a long time. Finally, Paul called the crew together
        and said, \u201CMen, you should have listened to me in the first place and
        not left Crete. You would have avoided all this damage and loss. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But take courage! None of you will lose your lives, even though the
        ship will go down. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For last night an angel of the God to whom I belong and whom I serve
        stood beside me, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and he said, \u2018Don\u2019t be afraid, Paul, for you will surely
        stand trial before Caesar! What\u2019s more, God in his goodness has granted
        safety to everyone sailing with you.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So take courage! For I believe God. It will be just as he said. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But we will be shipwrecked on an island.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Shipwreck
      content: 'About midnight on the fourteenth night of the storm, as we were being
        driven across the Sea of Adria,[COMMENT[0]] the sailors sensed land was near. '
      comments:
      - number: '27:27 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'The '
          body: 'Sea of Adria '
        - ft: includes the central portion of the Mediterranean.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'They dropped a weighted line and found that the water was 120 feet
        deep. But a little later they measured again and found it was only 90 feet
        deep.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:28 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: '20 fathoms . . . 15 fathoms '
        - ft: '[37 meters . . . 27 meters].'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'At this rate they were afraid we would soon be driven against the
        rocks along the shore, so they threw out four anchors from the back of the
        ship and prayed for daylight.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the sailors tried to abandon the ship; they lowered the lifeboat
        as though they were going to put out anchors from the front of the ship. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Paul said to the commanding officer and the soldiers, \u201CYou
        will all die unless the sailors stay aboard.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the soldiers cut the ropes to the lifeboat and let it drift away.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Just as day was dawning, Paul urged everyone to eat. \u201CYou have
        been so worried that you haven\u2019t touched food for two weeks,\u201D he
        said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlease eat something now for your own good. For not a hair
        of your heads will perish.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he took some bread, gave thanks to God before them all, and
        broke off a piece and ate it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then everyone was encouraged and began to eat\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'all 276 of us who were on board. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After eating, the crew lightened the ship further by throwing the
        cargo of wheat overboard.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When morning dawned, they didn\u2019t recognize the coastline, but
        they saw a bay with a beach and wondered if they could get to shore by running
        the ship aground. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they cut off the anchors and left them in the sea. Then they lowered
        the rudders, raised the foresail, and headed toward shore. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But they hit a shoal and ran the ship aground too soon. The bow of
        the ship stuck fast, while the stern was repeatedly smashed by the force
        of the waves and began to break apart.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The soldiers wanted to kill the prisoners to make sure they didn\u2019t
        swim ashore and escape. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the commanding officer wanted to spare Paul, so he didn\u2019t
        let them carry out their plan. Then he ordered all who could swim to jump
        overboard first and make for land. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: The others held on to planks or debris from the broken ship.[COMMENT[0]]
        So everyone escaped safely to shore.
      comments:
      - number: '27:44 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: "or were helped by members of the ship\u2019s crew."
  - verses:
    - title: Paul on the Island of Malta
      content: 'Once we were safe on shore, we learned that we were on the island
        of Malta. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people of the island were very kind to us. It was cold and rainy,
        so they built a fire on the shore to welcome us.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As Paul gathered an armful of sticks and was laying them on the fire,
        a poisonous snake, driven out by the heat, bit him on the hand. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people of the island saw it hanging from his hand and said to
        each other, \u201CA murderer, no doubt! Though he escaped the sea, justice
        will not permit him to live.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Paul shook off the snake into the fire and was unharmed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people waited for him to swell up or suddenly drop dead. But
        when they had waited a long time and saw that he wasn\u2019t harmed, they
        changed their minds and decided he was a god.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Near the shore where we landed was an estate belonging to Publius,
        the chief official of the island. He welcomed us and treated us kindly for
        three days. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As it happened, Publius\u2019s father was ill with fever and dysentery.
        Paul went in and prayed for him, and laying his hands on him, he healed him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then all the other sick people on the island came and were healed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As a result we were showered with honors, and when the time came
        to sail, people supplied us with everything we would need for the trip.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Arrives at Rome
      content: "It was three months after the shipwreck that we set sail on another
        ship that had wintered at the island\u2014an Alexandrian ship with the twin
        gods[COMMENT[0]] as its figurehead. "
      comments:
      - number: '28:11 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'The '
          body: 'twin gods '
        - ft: were the Roman gods Castor and Pollux.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'Our first stop was Syracuse,[COMMENT[0]] where we stayed three days. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Syracuse '
        - ft: was on the island of Sicily.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'From there we sailed across to Rhegium.[COMMENT[0]] A day later a
        south wind began blowing, so the following day we sailed up the coast to
        Puteoli. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'Rhegium '
        - ft: was on the southern tip of Italy.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'There we found some believers,[COMMENT[0]] who invited us to spend
        a week with them. And so we came to Rome.  '
      comments:
      - number: '28:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: brothers.
    - title: 
      content: 'The brothers and sisters[COMMENT[0]] in Rome had heard we were coming,
        and they came to meet us at the Forum[COMMENT[1]] on the Appian Way. Others
        joined us at The Three Taverns.[COMMENT[2]] When Paul saw them, he was encouraged
        and thanked God.  '
      comments:
      - number: '28:15a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Greek '
          body: brothers.
      - number: '28:15b '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'The Forum '
        - ft: was about 43 miles (70 kilometers) from Rome.
          body: 
      - number: '28:15c '
        contents:
        - ft: 
          body: 'The Three Taverns '
        - ft: was about 35 miles (57 kilometers) from Rome.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'When we arrived in Rome, Paul was permitted to have his own private
        lodging, though he was guarded by a soldier.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Paul Preaches at Rome under Guard
      content: "Three days after Paul\u2019s arrival, he called together the local
        Jewish leaders. He said to them, \u201CBrothers, I was arrested in Jerusalem
        and handed over to the Roman government, even though I had done nothing against
        our people or the customs of our ancestors. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Romans tried me and wanted to release me, because they found
        no cause for the death sentence. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the Jewish leaders protested the decision, I felt it necessary
        to appeal to Caesar, even though I had no desire to press charges against
        my own people. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I asked you to come here today so we could get acquainted and so
        I could explain to you that I am bound with this chain because I believe
        that the hope of Israel\u2014the Messiah\u2014has already come.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They replied, \u201CWe have had no letters from Judea or reports
        against you from anyone who has come here. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But we want to hear what you believe, for the only thing we know
        about this movement is that it is denounced everywhere.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So a time was set, and on that day a large number of people came
        to Paul\u2019s lodging. He explained and testified about the Kingdom of God
        and tried to persuade them about Jesus from the Scriptures. Using the law
        of Moses and the books of the prophets, he spoke to them from morning until
        evening. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some were persuaded by the things he said, but others did not believe. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And after they had argued back and forth among themselves, they left
        with this final word from Paul: \u201CThe Holy Spirit was right when he said
        to your ancestors through Isaiah the prophet,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Go and say to this people:\n\tWhen you hear what I say,\n\tyou
        will not understand.\n\tWhen you see what I do,\n\tyou will not comprehend.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the hearts of these people are hardened,\n\tand their ears cannot
        hear,\n\tand they have closed their eyes\u2014\n\tso their eyes cannot see,\n\tand
        their ears cannot hear,\n\tand their hearts cannot understand,\n\tand they
        cannot turn to me\n\tand let me heal them.\u2019[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '28:26-27 '
        contents:
        - ft: Isa 6:9-10 (Greek version).
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "So I want you to know that this salvation from God has also been
        offered to the Gentiles, and they will accept it.\u201D[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '28:28 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Some manuscripts add verse 29, '
          body: And when he had said these words, the Jews departed, greatly disagreeing
            with each other.
    - title: 
      content: 'For the next two years, Paul lived in Rome at his own expense.[COMMENT[0]]
        He welcomed all who visited him, '
      comments:
      - number: '28:30 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: in his own rented quarters.
    - title: 
      content: boldly proclaiming the Kingdom of God and teaching about the Lord
        Jesus Christ. And no one tried to stop him.
      comments: []
